[White "Introduction"]
[Black "The early moves"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A65"]
[PlyCount "22"]
[GameId "2160984178753480"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 $5 Bg7 ({•} 3... e5 {This move has been tried in an important game, Kramnik-Leko. We'll consider it in our Chapter 1.}) ({•} 3... Nc6 {In Chapter 1, we will study Black's alternatives to the most common 3...Bg7 and 3...d5 moves. For example, by playing 3...Nc6 Black tries to play in a non-standard way, where both sides need to make critical decisions already from the very first moves. For this reason, although Chapter 1 is about the 'sidelines', it will be an essential chapter.}) ({•} 3... d5 {Black wants to play the Grünfeld, but 3...d5 here is very different from 3...d5 against the standard 3. Nc3.} 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 {This is the starting position of our Grünfeld. As you can already see, White has a very nice center, and Black's typical central break, c7-c5, is very hard for him to achieve. On the other hand, against e7-e5, we'll almost always play d4-d5, where Black's bishop on g7 will lose important strength.} O-O {(7...Nc6 The Grünfeld sidelines will be investigated in Chapter 7. For example, the immediate 7...Nc6 has been recently played by GM Dubov, a renowned opening expert. )} 8. Qd2 Nc6 {(8...e5 9.d5 c6 This significant variation became famous after the Kramnik-Shirov match, but it became even more famous after the 2012 World Championship match Anand-Gelfand. In Chapter 6 we will present you a revolutionary new idea, which has never been tried in any game, and will definitely cause many troubles to your likely well-prepared opponents. )} 9. O-O-O Qd6 {This is a very serious line. Black's idea is to create fast pressure against our pawn on d4, for example, by playing ...Rd8 next. We will study it in Chapter 5. (9...e5 This is Black's old mainline, but nowadays, it is considered almost refuted. We'll study it in Chapter 2. ) (9...f5 By playing f7-f5, Black radically changes the central situation. 10.e5 Because of the inclusion of f5-e5, Black got a nice d5 square for his knight, but at the cost of a very passive bishop on g7. White's standard plan will be to launch a kingside attack with h4-h5. We'll study this variation in Chapter 3. 10...f4!? If in Chapter 3 we will discuss the 9...f5 variation, in Chapter 4 we will investigate only this 10...f4!? move. It's not a very popular move, and it has been played in only ten games, but it's a special one. Why? Because it has been played in the legendary match Stokfish-Alpha Zero, 2018. )}) 4. e4 d6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Nge2 {This is the starting position of the King's Indian section.} c5 ({•} 6... e5 {This is a typical move for Black in the KID, but against the Saemisch, it doesn't work so well. We will analyze it in Chapter 8.}) ({•} 6... c6 7. Be3 a6 {This one is an old variation; Black's idea is b7-b5. We will analyze it in Chapter 9.}) ({•} 6... Nc6 {This is named Panno Variation. It's a serious line, and we will study it in Chapter 10.}) ({•} 6... a6 7. Be3 {Now, Black can play} b5 {or 7...Nbd7 8.Qd2 b5 . This will be the topic of Chapter 11.}) 7. d5 e6 8. Ng3 exd5 9. cxd5 {This is the starting position for the KID/Benoni.} a6 (9... h5 {Black can also play 9...h5 without including the moves 9...a6 and 10. a4; we will analyze this option in Chapter 14.}) 10. a4 {The moves 9...a6 and 10. a4 are often played automatically by both players, but in this course, we will see that this sequence is extremely significant. Whether these moves are included or not will have a profound impact on the game for both sides.} h5 {This is Black's typical continuation, which comes with different strategic ideas.} (10... Nbd7 11. Be2 Rb8 {This one is quite serious. Black is aiming for the Ne8-Nc7-b5 maneuver, and in fact, they might even start with 11...Ne8. We will analyze this in Chapter 16.}) 11. Be2 Nh7 {This is Black's best continuation, in my opinion; we will analyze it in Chapter 13.} ({•} 11... h4 {This would be Black's most natural continuation; we will analyze it in Chapter 12.}) ({•} 11... Nbd7 12. Bg5 {This line, along with some other minor sidelines, will be analyzed in Chapter 15.}) *

