1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} (3. f3 {The main continuations for Black are} d5 {(Grünfeld,) 3...Bg7 (King's Indian, and) 3...c5 (Benoni/King's Indian. In the first Chapter, we will explore Black's alternatives.)}) 3... d6 4. Nc3 (4. Nc3 {Black can still play} Bg7 {, where after} 5. e4 {, we will transpose into the main King's Indian position.}) 4... e5 {This sideline has been played only twice, but in two high-level games: Wang vs. Nepomniachtchi in 2011 and Savchenko vs. Sindarov in 2024.} 5. Bg5 {[%cal Rd4e5] We are now threatening 6.dxe5 because after 6...dxe5 7.Qxd8 Kxd8 , Black's knight on f6 will be hanging.} (5. d5 $6 e4 $1 {∞ Black has good counterplay.}) 5... exd4 $6 6. Bxf6 $1 (6. Qxd4 {It is also good enough for a small advantage.} Bg7 7. e4 {⩲}) 6... Qxf6 7. Nd5 Qd8 8. Qxd4 {Black has some serious problems.} f6 {The only move.} 9. Nxf6+ Kf7 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. Qf4+ $14 {[%cal Ge1c1] White can continue with long castle, and Black doesn't have enough compensation for the missing pawn.} *

