1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} (3. f3 {The main continuations for Black are} d5 {(Grünfeld,) 3...Bg7 (King's Indian, and) 3...c5 (Benoni/King's Indian. In the first Chapter, we will explore Black's alternatives.)}) 3... Nc6 (3... Nc6 {This is Black's most common sideline. The idea is to respond to} 4. e4 {with} e5 {.}) ({The obvious drawback of the move} 3... Nc6 {is that after} 4. d5 {, the knight will have to waste tempos finding a safe square. On the other hand, Black hopes to gain something from provoking the d4-d5 push; often, they will try to challenge our pawn on d5 by playing c7-c6 or e7-e6.}) 4. d5 Ne5 5. e4 {[%cal Gf3f4]} d6 {White was threatening f3-f4, so Black had to create an escape square on d7 for their knight on e5.} 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. f4 Ned7 8. Nh3 $1 {[%cal Gh3f2] A very important move. Since we have played the ambitious f3-f4, we must be aware that our pawn on e4 could become vulnerable in the near future. By playing 8. Nh3, we can maneuver our knight to f2, where it will securely defend the e4 pawn. I want to point out that Nh3 should be played immediately because, for the moment, Black's knight is on d7. If we delay Nh3 in favor of another development move, Black could play Nc5, making Nh3 impossible due to Bxh3.} O-O 9. Nf2 Nc5 10. Be2 {Both sides have made their desired development moves, and it's challenging to imagine any other significant deviations. But now Black must decide whether to continue with c7-c6 or e7-e6.} (10. Be2 {I want to point out that, for practical purposes, it makes no difference to us whether Black plays} e5 {or 10...e6 because in both cases, we will continue with 11.dxe6 .}) 10... e6 11. dxe6 $1 (11. O-O {is White's most common continuation, but after} exd5 12. cxd5 c6 $1 {Black has good counterplay.}) 11... fxe6 {Now, Black has greater control of the center, but the king might be weaker in the future. For this reason, it is logical for White to prepare for long castling. Once castled, we can proceed with the h4-h5 plan.} 12. Be3 b6 {Black supports their knight and wants to develop their bishop to b7.} (12... Nfd7 $6 13. h4 $1 {followed by h4-h5.}) 13. Qc2 Bb7 14. O-O-O Nfd7 {This move has been played against me by the solid Croatian GM Bogdan Lalic in 2019.} 15. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5] White is again very fast in creating an attack on the kingside.} *

