1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} (3. f3 {The main continuations for Black are} d5 {(Grünfeld,) 3...Bg7 (King's Indian, and) 3...c5 (Benoni/King's Indian. In the first Chapter, we will explore Black's alternatives.)}) 3... d5 {Black has several other minor options on move 3, with the most common being 3...Nc6. We analyze all of them in Chapter 1.} 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 {This is the starting position of our Grünfeld Variation.} Nc6 9. O-O-O e5 {Once, this was Black's main line. On the other hand, the continuation e5-d5-Nd4 was considered a standard and natural sequence before the advent of computers. Today, it is well known that in this variation, Black cannot resolve their opening issues. Consequently, this line has been gradually abandoned in favor of other approaches, which we will explore in the following chapters.} 10. d5 Nd4 {[%cal Gc7c6] This is the starting position of the 9...e5 line. Black's idea is to play c7-c6, challenging our center. It's extremely important for us to not allow them the time to do it.} 11. f4 $1 {[%csl Rd4] We are challenging the stability of Black's knight on d4.} Bg4 {This developing move is gaining a tempo against our rook on d1, and at the same time, it prevents Nf3 ideas.} 12. Re1 c5 {Understanding that the pawn on e5 won't provide sufficient stability for the knight on d4, Black has no choice but to support it with the c-pawn.} 13. fxe5 Bxe5 14. h3 $1 {As soon as Black's bishop leaves the d1-h5 diagonal, we can proceed with Nf3!} Bd7 {This is Black's main continuation, but it's clearly a concession as now we can continue with the desired Nf3!} 15. Nf3 Nxf3 16. gxf3 {The key point is that White's center is now very solid, and the plan of h4-h5 appears strong and imminent. It's not at all clear, if not impossible, how Black can create adequate counterplay.} (16. gxf3 {In Chapter 2 we will analyze} Re8 {, 16...Na4 and 16...f5 , starting here.}) *

