1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} (3. f3 {The main continuations for Black are} d5 {(Grünfeld,) 3...Bg7 (King's Indian, and) 3...c5 (Benoni/King's Indian. In the first Chapter, we will explore Black's alternatives.)}) 3... d5 {Black has several other minor options on move 3, with the most common being 3...Nc6. We analyze all of them in Chapter 1.} 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 {This is the starting position of our Grünfeld Variation.} Nc6 9. O-O-O f5 {In this chapter, we will examine 9...f5, which is Black's most common move. Black has a cunning plan in mind: fxe4 followed by fxe4 and then Nxd4! The danger lies in the fact that after the exchanges on d4, our bishop on f1 will be left unprotected.} 10. e5 {This is the most principled continuation for White. Now, Black's bishop is temporarily out of play, blocked by our pawns on d4 and e5, but Black has gained control of the important d5 square for their pieces. White's typical plan will be to continue with h4-h5, aiming to launch a quick attack on the kingside.} (10. h4 $5 {An interesting and very aggressive move. Black must be well-prepared for the correct follow-up, but if so, it will be difficult for White to gain an advantage.} fxe4 11. h5 gxh5 $1 {Black's best continuation.} 12. Rxh5 Bf5 13. Rg5 $5 {We are threatening Rxg7+, but after} Bg6 {I couldn't find anything satisfactory for White to fight for an advantage.}) 10... Nb4 {This is by far the most frequently played move by Black, and it aligns perfectly with the strategy of playing for control of the d5 square.} (10... Be6 $4 {That would be a serious mistake due to} 11. d5 $1 {+- .}) 11. Nh3 $1 {Our knight is looking for the g5 or f4 squares, depending on the situation.} Be6 {This is the most played move and also the most logical one available for Black, as it develops a piece while simultaneously gaining control of the important d5 square.} 12. Kb1 {We have already learned from the Carlsen-Li Chao game the importance of Rb1! as a prophylactic move.} Qd7 {The most played move, and also the best for Black. It is certainly a useful move, with one of its associated ideas being to play Na4, aiming to create counterplay on the queenside.} 13. Nf4 $1 {Now, Black has two important theoretical options: 13... Bf7 and 13... Rfd8.} (13. Ng5 $6 {It might seem more logical than 13. Nf4, but it doesn't work due to concrete reasons:} Nc4 $1 14. Qc1 Nxe3 15. Qxe3 Bh6 $1 {∞ In 13. Nf4, we will see the same position but with our knight on f4. This changes everything because we will then have the opportunity to play 16. d5!, which is not possible in the current position.}) 13... Rfd8 {This move has been played in slightly fewer games than 13... Bf7, but I believe it is the best continuation for Black.} 14. a3 a5 $1 15. d5 $1 {White's critical continuation. We are temporarily sacrificing a pawn, exploiting the fact that due to the multiple pins, Black will not be able to stabilize without incurring greater material losses.} (15. Bb5 $2 {Now this idea is not as good as after 13... Bf7, because after} c6 16. d5 {Black can play} N6xd5 $1 {as after} 17. axb4 Nxf4 $1 {-+ the queen on d7 is defended twice.}) 15... N4xd5 16. Ncxd5 Nxd5 17. Bc4 c6 {Black's only move.} 18. Bb6 $1 {Exploiting the pins.} Bh6 $1 {Black, in turn, creates an important pin, which will allow them to enter a disadvantageous but possibly defensible position.} 19. Bxd8 Rxd8 20. g3 {We have to defend our knight.} Bxf4 21. gxf4 {It is not easy to determine whether this position is a fortress or not. White will continue by exchanging the strong knight on d5 with Bxd5, then proceed with h4-h5 to try and create counterplay on the kingside. For now, it's difficult to activate our rooks, but in a practical game, this might become feasible if Black doesn’t remain passive and mistakenly tries to create counterplay on the queenside by pushing pawns; this would actually help White find ways to activate the rooks. If Black remains passive, which is probably their best strategy, we can play a long game with no risk.} *

