1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} (3. f3 {The main continuations for Black are} d5 {(Grünfeld,) 3...Bg7 (King's Indian, and) 3...c5 (Benoni/King's Indian. In the first Chapter, we will explore Black's alternatives.)}) 3... d5 {Black has several other minor options on move 3, with the most common being 3...Nc6. We analyze all of them in Chapter 1.} 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 {This is the starting position of our Grünfeld Variation.} Nc6 9. O-O-O f5 10. e5 f4 $5 {This move was first played in the 2018 Stockfish vs. AlphaZero match. It involves a pawn sacrifice that offers long-term compensation, something too deep to be fully grasped by any human or computer until that point. The first player to use this move in a practical game was the Grünfeld expert GM Emil Sutovsky, who played it a few months later in 2018.} 11. Bxf4 Nb4 {The move that was played by AlphaZero in the aforementioned game.} 12. a3 {Stockfish plays the most critical move in the position. This choice demonstrates the engine's precise calculation and deep understanding of the position, challenging AlphaZero's strategy and testing the depth of its long-term compensation plan. The game exemplifies the high level of play and the intense competition between these two advanced chess engines, where each move is a blend of tactical sharpness and strategic foresight.} Nc6 $1 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Gc6a5] An incredible understanding. Black has sacrificed a pawn and lost two tempi, but now White's b3 square is weakened. Black can aim for a knight on a5 and take advantage of the light squares to create counterplay.} 13. g3 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Gf1h3] A very strong novelty. The key point is that our bishop on f4 is now protected. Sometimes, we might also have Bh3 ideas.} (13. Nge2 {This is the move played by Stockfish, but after} Na5 {∞ Black has both the ideas of Nb3 and Nc4, and now has excellent compensation for the pawn. The game between Stockfish and AlphaZero ultimately ended in a draw.}) 13... Na5 14. Qd3 $14 (14. Qd3 {Black's position is far from easy to play. Probably the best continuation is} c5 {, where after} 15. dxc5 {, Black can exchange queens and try to defend the endgame. This is more than enough for us to conclude that the move 11...Nb4, played by AlphaZero in 2018, is very interesting and strategically deep, but it offers White excellent practical chances if well-prepared.}) *

