1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} (3. f3 {The main continuations for Black are} d5 {(Grünfeld,) 3...Bg7 (King's Indian, and) 3...c5 (Benoni/King's Indian. In the first Chapter, we will explore Black's alternatives.)}) 3... d5 {Black has several other minor options on move 3, with the most common being 3...Nc6. We analyze all of them in Chapter 1.} 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 {This is the starting position of our Grünfeld Variation.} Nc6 9. O-O-O Qd6 ({Unlike the historically well-known moves} 9... e5 {and 9...f5 , this move is relatively new to chess theory. It was first played in the game Mamedyarov-Petrosian Tigran in 2004. The idea behind this move for Black is to follow up with ...Rd8, putting immediate pressure on the d4 pawn. Today, this line is considered the most promising way for Black to equalize the game.}) 10. Nb5 $1 {This move may seem artificial at first glance, but it allows us to defend our d4 pawn while gaining a tempo against Black's queen on d6.} Qd7 {Naturally, Black doesn't want to play 10...Qd8, as their plan relies on the quick development of the rook to d8.} 11. Bh6 {This move is less commonly played compared to 11. Kb1, but it doesn't offer fewer chances to fight for an advantage. From a practical standpoint, the positions arising from 11. Bh6 are more manageable and easier to understand, and the theoretical variations are fewer and simpler to memorize.} a6 $6 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. Nc3 {Black's position is very difficult.} e5 {The only logical move to create counterplay; however, it is not enough.} 14. d5 Nd4 15. f4 $1 f6 16. h4 $16 {[%cal Gg1f3,Gh4h5] Black is still in serious trouble. White's next move could be h4-h5 or Nf3.} *

