1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} (3. f3 {The main continuations for Black are} d5 {(Grünfeld,) 3...Bg7 (King's Indian, and) 3...c5 (Benoni/King's Indian. In the first Chapter, we will explore Black's alternatives.)}) 3... d5 {Black has several other minor options on move 3, with the most common being 3...Nc6. We analyze all of them in Chapter 1.} 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 {This is the starting position of our Grünfeld Variation.} Nc6 9. O-O-O Qd6 ({Unlike the historically well-known moves} 9... e5 {and 9...f5 , this move is relatively new to chess theory. It was first played in the game Mamedyarov-Petrosian Tigran in 2004. The idea behind this move for Black is to follow up with ...Rd8, putting immediate pressure on the d4 pawn. Today, this line is considered the most promising way for Black to equalize the game.}) 10. Nb5 $1 {This move may seem artificial at first glance, but it allows us to defend our d4 pawn while gaining a tempo against Black's queen on d6.} Qd7 {Naturally, Black doesn't want to play 10...Qd8, as their plan relies on the quick development of the rook to d8.} 11. Bh6 {This move is less commonly played compared to 11. Kb1, but it doesn't offer fewer chances to fight for an advantage. From a practical standpoint, the positions arising from 11. Bh6 are more manageable and easier to understand, and the theoretical variations are fewer and simpler to memorize.} Bxh6 $1 {Black's best and only move.} 12. Qxh6 {The point is that Black can now win the d4 pawn. He must do so to have any chances, although they will need to be very precise to resolve the pin on the d-file.} a6 13. Nc3 Nxd4 14. f4 $1 {A very important move. Otherwise, Black would have continued with e7-e5.} f6 $1 {[%cal Ge7e5] Black is once again preparing e7-e5. However, it's clear that the inclusion of the moves f4-f6 favors White.} 15. Nf3 (15. h4 {This move is very logical, but after} e5 $1 16. h5 Qg7 $1 {Black is OK.}) 15... e5 $1 {Black sacrifices a pawn, but White will have to lose some time to capture it.} 16. fxe5 {Capturing the pawn is the most ambitious continuation.} fxe5 17. Nxe5 Qd6 18. Nf3 c5 {White has managed to recapture the sacrificed pawn, but meanwhile, Black has continued development and stabilized the knight on d4. While Black's position remains very risky from a human perspective, the computer is able to find sufficient resources to defend.} (18... c5 {My main recommendation is} 19. Bd3 {, a move played by Caruana in December 2023, but I would also like to explore with you the more concrete moves 19.Ng5 and 19.h4 .}) 19. Bd3 $5 {A very interesting move that was played in a rapid game between Caruana and MVL in December 2023.} (19. Ng5 {Now Black will need to play a few precise moves, but the final position will be entirely acceptable for them.} Qe7 $1 {(( 19...Qc7? 20.Na4!! Nxa4 21.Bc4+ +- ))} 20. Nd5 $5 {White's logical continuation. (( 20.Na4?? Nxa4 21.Bc4+ Be6 -+ Now Black's queen on e7 is defending the bishop on e6.))} Nxd5 21. Bc4 Kh8 22. Bxd5 Qg7 23. Qxg7+ Kxg7 24. Rdf1 {The endgame is equal. You can see more details here.}) *

