1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} (3. f3 {The main continuations for Black are} d5 {(Grünfeld,) 3...Bg7 (King's Indian, and) 3...c5 (Benoni/King's Indian. In the first Chapter, we will explore Black's alternatives.)}) 3... d5 {Black has several other minor options on move 3, with the most common being 3...Nc6. We analyze all of them in Chapter 1.} 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 {This is the starting position of our Grünfeld Variation.} e5 $5 {Black plays 8...e5 immediately, without first playing Nc6, with the idea that when we play 9. d5, Black can continue with 9...c6, immediately challenging our center. This idea was first seen back in 1933 in the game between Reuben Fine and Arthur Dake. However, it only gained fame in 1998 following the game Kramnik-Shirov, where Black emerged victorious.The most famous games in this variation are undoubtedly Anand-Gelfand in 2012, played in the third game of the World Championship match, and the 2016 Candidates Tournament game between Anish Giri and Fabiano Caruana. As you can see, this is a line with a lot of history!} 9. d5 c6 10. h4 $1 {There was an old saying: 'Against a flank attack, a counterattack in the center is usually strong,' but here things are reversed! 'Against a central attack, a flank attack is strong.'} cxd5 11. exd5 N8d7 {[%csl Gg8,Gh7][%cal Gd7f6,Yf6g8,Yf6h7] This is by far Black's main move. The idea is to transfer the knight to f6, where it will join the defense of Black's king.} (11... h5 12. g4 $1 {Transposes to 10...h5 lines.}) 12. h5 Nf6 (12... gxh5 {A computer move, but white is better anyway after} 13. Bh6 {⩲ or 13.O-O-O .}) 13. h6 {Instead of following the highly theoretical path that begins with 13. hxg6, where there are over 200 high-level games, and you would need to memorize numerous lines—likely facing equally well-prepared opponents—I suggest 13. h6!?. This move has never been played before and offers White excellent chances to fight for an advantage. The fantastic aspect for us is that it’s highly unlikely our opponent will be prepared for this, and without proper preparation, playing as Black will not be easy at all.} (13. hxg6 fxg6 14. O-O-O Bd7 15. Kb1 Rc8 16. d6 e4 $1 {Black sacrifices a pawn, but the dark-squares bishop will be strong.} 17. fxe4 Ng4 $1 18. Bg5 Qe8 19. Nf3 {Where Black's best move is} Rf7 $3 {There are more than 50 games in this position, and although White has several interesting options, most of these have been extensively analyzed and are well known to experienced Grünfeld players.}) 13... Bh8 14. Rd1 $1 {[%csl Gd5] We need to defend the pawn on d5, but at the same time, we don't want to commit our king to c1, where it could be more exposed to counterplay with moves like Bf5 and Rc8.} ({After} 14. O-O-O $6 Bd7 {(( 14...Bf5!? ))} 15. Kb1 Rc8 {Black has some initiative.}) 14... Re8 $1 {[%cal Ge5e4] This is the most precise continuation for Black. The idea is quite clear: e5-e4, which would open up the dark-squared bishop without even sacrificing a pawn.} (14... Nh5 $2 {Black attempts to exploit the weakened g3 square, but it doesn't lead to anything favorable for Black.} 15. Kf2 f5 16. Nh3 {±}) (14... Bf5 $6 {It might seem like an active square for the bishop, but after} 15. g4 $1 {± Black has nothing better than retreating the bishop to d7, and the move g2-g4 is undoubtedly useful for White.}) 15. Ne4 $1 {We need to play this move to stop the strong positional idea of e5-e4.} Bf5 {The logical continuation for Black, aiming to fight for the important e4 square.} 16. Bb5 $1 {A very strong move that prevents Black from advancing their plans unchallenged.} Bd7 {This is Black's most human continuation, in my opinion.} 17. Bxd7 Qxd7 18. b3 $14 {Now that the light-squares bishops have been exchanged, this move is very important because we need to keep control of the c4 square. [Nxfd5] is not possible because of Bxb6, while [Nbxd5] is not possible because of Nxf6+. If Black places a rook on d8, Bg5! becomes very strong.} *

