1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} (3. f3 {The main continuations for Black are} d5 {(Grünfeld,) 3...Bg7 (King's Indian, and) 3...c5 (Benoni/King's Indian. In the first Chapter, we will explore Black's alternatives.)}) 3... Bg7 4. e4 O-O 5. Nc3 d6 (5... d6 {This is the starting position of the Saemisch Variation in the King's Indian Defense. The most common moves played by White here are} 6. Be3 {and 6.Bg5 . However, during my career, I have always preferred 6.Nge2 . The reason is that it keeps the bishop on c1 flexible. Depending on the situation, the bishop might move to e3, g5, or stay on c1 for a while, giving us time to focus on other important moves.}) 6. Nge2 e5 {This is the typical continuation for Black in the King's Indian Defense, and many classic games have been played from this position. However, nowadays, the move e7-e5 is rarely seen when White opts for the Saemisch system.Even though this variation has fallen out of favor, I believe it’s still important to dedicate a chapter to it, as it was once played by some of the strongest players in the world.} 7. Bg5 ({If we were to follow the engine blindly, we would see that} 7. Bg5 {is considered slightly weaker than 7.d5 . However, having played this position throughout my life, I can assure you that from a practical standpoint, this isn’t the case. The move 7.Bg5 is much easier for us to play. The engine suggests that Black is only slightly worse after 7...exd4 , but exd4 leads to a pawn structure that any strong chess player would find very comfortable for White and rather passive for Black.This is why it's crucial not to rely solely on the engine, but to always try to understand the position with a human perspective.}) 7... exd4 {Let's start by analyzing Black's best move according to the engine.} 8. Nxd4 Nc6 9. Nc2 $5 {As we have some extra space, I like keeping all four knights on the board.} h6 $1 {Black's most precise continuation.} (9... Be6 10. Be2 Ne5 11. Ne3 h6 12. Bh4 {⩲}) 10. Be3 Be6 11. Be2 Ne5 {[%csl Rc4] Black attacks our c4 pawn.} 12. b3 c6 {This move has been played in the only three games that have reached this position.} 13. O-O Re8 (13... d5 $2 {Black is not ready for the d6-d5 break.} 14. Bd4 Qc7 15. f4 {±}) 14. Qe1 $14 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Ga1d1] Our idea is to place a rook on d1 so that it will be very difficult for Black to play d6-d5. Without d6-d5, Black's position is simply worse.} *

