1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} (3. f3 {The main continuations for Black are} d5 {(Grünfeld,) 3...Bg7 (King's Indian, and) 3...c5 (Benoni/King's Indian. In the first Chapter, we will explore Black's alternatives.)}) 3... Bg7 4. e4 O-O 5. Nc3 d6 (5... d6 {This is the starting position of the Saemisch Variation in the King's Indian Defense. The most common moves played by White here are} 6. Be3 {and 6.Bg5 . However, during my career, I have always preferred 6.Nge2 . The reason is that it keeps the bishop on c1 flexible. Depending on the situation, the bishop might move to e3, g5, or stay on c1 for a while, giving us time to focus on other important moves.}) 6. Nge2 e5 {This is the typical continuation for Black in the King's Indian Defense, and many classic games have been played from this position. However, nowadays, the move e7-e5 is rarely seen when White opts for the Saemisch system.Even though this variation has fallen out of favor, I believe it’s still important to dedicate a chapter to it, as it was once played by some of the strongest players in the world.} 7. Bg5 ({If we were to follow the engine blindly, we would see that} 7. Bg5 {is considered slightly weaker than 7.d5 . However, having played this position throughout my life, I can assure you that from a practical standpoint, this isn’t the case. The move 7.Bg5 is much easier for us to play. The engine suggests that Black is only slightly worse after 7...exd4 , but exd4 leads to a pawn structure that any strong chess player would find very comfortable for White and rather passive for Black.This is why it's crucial not to rely solely on the engine, but to always try to understand the position with a human perspective.}) 7... c6 $5 {Historically, this has been Black's most common continuation.} 8. Qd2 (8. d5 {was also possible. We will likely continue with d4-d5 later, even after 8. Qd2, but I prefer to make a useful move first, waiting one more move to see how Black continues.}) 8... Nbd7 9. d5 {I would prefer to wait another move before playing d4-d5, but I can't find any good moves that are always useful, like 8. Qd2. For example, White's second-best move according to the engine is 9. Rd1, but I don't like it because then I will not have the long castle option anymore. So, objectively, now is the time for 9. d5.} cxd5 (9... c5 $6 {This move was played in the classical game Tal-Tolush in 1957, but after} 10. g4 {+- Black's position is lost from a strategic point of view because he is unable to create any counterplay.}) 10. cxd5 (10. Nxd5 $5 {It’s another equally good option for White.}) 10... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gd7b6,Gb6c4] Black's plan is to continue with b7-b5 and then Nb6-Nc4.} 11. Nc1 $1 {A strong move. We are preparing against b7-b5.} b5 12. b4 {Even though the engine considers the move 12. Nd3 to be slightly more precise, I still like the plan used in the game Basso-Hollan, 2019.} (12. Nd3 $5 {This is White's best move according to the engine. Now, Black is unable to place a knight on c5.} Nb6 13. b3 {±}) 12... Nb6 13. Nb3 $1 {[%cal Gb3a5,Ga5c6,Ga5c4] White's knight will reach the a5 square, from where it will control the important c4 and c6 squares.} (13. Nb3 {For example,} Bd7 14. Na5 {± as in Basso-Hollan, 2019.}) *

