1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} (3. f3 {The main continuations for Black are} d5 {(Grünfeld,) 3...Bg7 (King's Indian, and) 3...c5 (Benoni/King's Indian. In the first Chapter, we will explore Black's alternatives.)}) 3... Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Nge2 Nc6 7. Be3 a6 {This is the starting position of the so-called Panno Variation. Black's idea is to push b7-b5. It is a positional line, and instead of memorizing a lot of variations, you should focus on understanding the ideas and plans.} 8. Qd2 {[%csl Gd2] This move is always useful for White in the Saemisch systems.} Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5] Historically, this has been Black's main move. The idea is quite clear: b7-b5.} 9. Rc1 $1 {This is an important prophylactic move. The idea is that now Black cannot play b7-b5 because of the hanging knight on c6.} (9. Rb1 {This would be our move in case of 7...Bd7, but here it’s not as effective because after} b5 10. cxb5 axb5 11. b4 {Black is in time to play} e5 $1 12. d5 Ne7 {∞ This position occurred in my game against Efimenko back in 2002. Although I managed to win that game, Black's position is objectively good. He can continue with Bd7, followed by Bc6.}) 9... Bd7 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Gb7b5] This is Black's logical continuation. Now the knight on c6 is protected, and Black is ready for b7-b5; that's why our next move is very important.} 10. Nd1 $1 (10. Nd1 {This is a very strong positional move. Generally, our knight is ideally placed on the f2 square, but in this case, the main idea is that after} b5 {, we can continue with} 11. c5 {. If Black responds with dxc5, we can recapture with the rook. This is a crucial detail because if we had to recapture with the pawn, our position would not be so good. By recapturing with the rook, we maintain a strong center and can use our rook on the c file to apply pressure.}) 10... b5 (10... Re8 11. Nf2 b5 12. c5 {transposes.}) 11. c5 Re8 {This is Black’s strongest move according to the engine. The idea is to follow up with dxc5-Rxc5, and now, thanks to the rook on e8, the move e7-e5 will become possible.} 12. Nf2 {[%cal Gf2d3] As usual, we maneuver the knight to the f2 square, where it is perfectly placed and may later move to d3, supporting control over the c5 square.} dxc5 13. Rxc5 e5 {This was Black's idea behind the move 11...Re8.} 14. d5 Ne7 {[%cal Gc7c6] Now Black wants to play c7-c6, and it’s crucial for us to prevent this; otherwise, our opponent could solve his positional problems.} 15. Qc1 $1 Bf8 {Black wants their bishop to maintain control over the c5 square.} 16. Bg5 $5 {This is a typically strong move, as the pin Nf6-Qd8 can be troublesome for Black in some variations.} (16. Rxc7 $6 {allows Black to enter a complicated position.} Nexd5 $1 17. exd5 Nxd5 18. Rc2 Bf5 {∞ .}) 16... Nc8 (16... Nc8 {Now White can play} 17. Rc2 {and we will be slightly better, but I also like the following creative idea.}) 17. Nd3 $5 (17. Rxc7 Bb4+ {∞}) 17... Bxc5 18. Nxc5 $14 {[%csl Gg5,Gc5,Ra6,Rf6,Rg7,Rh6][%cal Gg2g4,Gh2h4,Gh4h5,Ge2g3] We’ve sacrificed the exchange, but now Black has serious problems on the dark squares. We can continue with h4-h5 to launch a quick attack against the opponent’s king, and for the moment, the a6 pawn is also hanging. White has excellent play, but of course, feel free to play 17. Rc2 if you prefer, where you’ll simply have a slight advantage.} *

