1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} (3. f3 {The main continuations for Black are} d5 {(Grünfeld,) 3...Bg7 (King's Indian, and) 3...c5 (Benoni/King's Indian. In the first Chapter, we will explore Black's alternatives.)}) 3... Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Nge2 a6 7. Be3 b5 {Usually, Black plays the moves ...b5 and ...Nbd7 starting with either one, but be careful! We reply differently to them.} 8. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5] In this case, White is ready to push h4-h5. Since Black revealed their cards by playing immediately ...b5, also we can do the same just on the other side of the board.} (8. Qd2 {is a possible move, but the problem is that after} c6 {White is transposing into the line with ...a6-c6 where instead of g4, White played Qd2. This version is an improved one for the Black side, though one can still argue that White has the advantage here. I suggest we go for a different approach.}) 8... h5 {Black should stop a white pawn coming to h5.} 9. Nf4 {We have seen this move in a similar position, the knight on f4 is a strong piece, and it is hard to kick it with ...e5, because that just further weakens the d5 square.} b4 {This is the best choice, but I should say it is already a tough move to play. Usually Black likes to keep the tension, not release it, since now White has a very strong pawn center.} 10. Ncd5 Nc6 {Not a preffered square for the knight, but honestly Black couldn't waste another tempo on a pawn move to protect b4.} 11. Nxf6+ {It is in White's interest to trade the pair of knights, so that g4 will be easier to achieve.} Bxf6 12. Qd2 e5 {The only move that justifies the placement of Black's pieces. Also seemingly it wins the pawn on h4!} 13. dxe5 Nxe5 (13... Bxh4+ {Of course, this is met with Rxh4! and Black's position is dubious. You will find it here.}) 14. O-O-O $14 {[%cal Gf1e2,Gc1b1,Gg2g4,Gc4c5] The Maroczy Bind offers White a stable advantage, our next move will most probably be c5. You shouldn't worry too much about an attack on the queenside, because any ...b3 push is met with a3 and the structure is rock solid, while a potential g4 is much more scary for Black to face. You can practice these type of positions also to get more experience and develop a feeling for where the pieces should go.} *

