1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} (3. f3 {The main continuations for Black are} d5 {(Grünfeld,) 3...Bg7 (King's Indian, and) 3...c5 (Benoni/King's Indian. In the first Chapter, we will explore Black's alternatives.)}) 3... c5 4. d5 e6 {As we will see in the 'Move Order Training', Black has many different move orders, but the final position at move nine will always be the same.} 5. e4 d6 {Black prevents e4-e5 ideas.} 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Nge2 {White's plan is to develop the knight to g3.} O-O 8. Ng3 exd5 9. cxd5 {This is the main position of the KID/Benoni variations.} a6 10. a4 h5 {Black's second most popular move. It is logical for Black to play against our knight on g3, since it may not have a lot of retreat squares.} 11. Be2 {We are not concerned about h5-h4 at this moment. Since we have not yet castled, our knight can retreat to f1. From f1, it can move to e3 and eventually reach the excellent c4 square.} (11. Bg5 {is another possible move, with the idea to stop h5-h4. We will speak about this move in a separate Chapter.}) 11... h4 {In this chapter, we will examine the consequences of this logical continuation. As I mentioned earlier, we do not fear this move, but it remains a serious option for Black.} 12. Nf1 {Now, Black reaches a big crossroads; essentially, they must choose between two plans: one is to ignore White's idea of going Bg5 that targets the h4 pawn and focus on achieving ... b7-b5, the other one is to retreat the f6 knight, this way protecting the g5 square and focus on the ...f7-f5 push eventually.} Nbd7 {This is the best according to the engines.} 13. Bg5 h3 {Now White has to take an important decision. Usually the options are g3, g4, gxh3 or the more sophisticated Ne3-hxg2-Rg1.} 14. gxh3 $1 {To understand why it is the best, we had to compare it with other options.} Rb8 (14... Qc7 {Black now wants to continue with Nh5, but we can prevent this idea by playing.} 15. Ng3 {⩲}) 15. Ne3 $1 {This is still the best square for our knight.} (15. Ng3 $6 {has been chosen by Ivanchuk, but here Black has his typical break.} b5 $1 16. axb5 axb5 17. Nxb5 Qb6 {Black has full compensation.}) 15... b5 (15... Qc7 {Of course now we don't fear Nh7-g5 ideas, as our bishop has many squares compared to the 14. g3 line.} 16. O-O Nh7 17. Bh4 {±}) 16. axb5 {Here White should remember some lines, but keep in mind that this position was never seen in practice.} axb5 17. Nxb5 Qb6 {Black defends the d6 pawn and at the same time unpins the knight on f6.} 18. Na3 {Black has some moves, but none of them leads to equality.} Qb4+ {White now must give up castling rights.} (18... Nxe4 $6 {This sacrifice doesn't work anymore.} 19. fxe4 Qb4+ 20. Kf2 Qxe4 21. Qd3 Qe5 22. Rhg1 $1 {+-}) 19. Kf2 $1 (19. Qd2 $6 {would be a mistake due to} Nxe4 $1 20. fxe4 Bxb2 {where Black is for sure not worse.}) (19. Kf2 {Now, after} Ne5 {White has two extra pawns, and all he needs to do now is to consolidate. You can go deeper here.}) (19. Kf2 Nh5 {is also possible; you can explore the line here.}) *

