1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} (3. f3 {The main continuations for Black are} d5 {(Grünfeld,) 3...Bg7 (King's Indian, and) 3...c5 (Benoni/King's Indian. In the first Chapter, we will explore Black's alternatives.)}) 3... c5 4. d5 e6 {As we will see in the 'Move Order Training', Black has many different move orders, but the final position at move nine will always be the same.} 5. e4 d6 {Black prevents e4-e5 ideas.} 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Nge2 {White's plan is to develop the knight to g3.} O-O 8. Ng3 exd5 9. cxd5 {This is the main position of the KID/Benoni variations.} a6 10. a4 h5 {Black's second most popular move. It is logical for Black to play against our knight on g3, since it may not have a lot of retreat squares.} 11. Be2 {We are not concerned about h5-h4 at this moment. Since we have not yet castled, our knight can retreat to f1. From f1, it can move to e3 and eventually reach the excellent c4 square.} (11. Bg5 {is another possible move, with the idea to stop h5-h4. We will speak about this move in a separate Chapter.}) 11... h4 {In this chapter, we will examine the consequences of this logical continuation. As I mentioned earlier, we do not fear this move, but it remains a serious option for Black.} 12. Nf1 {Now, Black reaches a big crossroads; essentially, they must choose between two plans: one is to ignore White's idea of going Bg5 that targets the h4 pawn and focus on achieving ... b7-b5, the other one is to retreat the f6 knight, this way protecting the g5 square and focus on the ...f7-f5 push eventually.} Nh7 {This is the most common move in the position and very much in the spirit. Black not only takes control of the g5 square, but also opens their bishop on g7 and prepares the f7-f5 push. The downside is that it is time consuming and Black's knight on h7 can be misplaced at some point.} 13. Ne3 $1 {[%cal Ge3c4] We make use of the fact that we still didn't develop our bishop to e3. Now if Black wastes one more move, they will end up in big trouble.} Nd7 $1 {An absolutely necessary move. Black has to be able to meet White's Nc4 with Ne5! to eliminate the pressure on the d6 pawn.} 14. O-O (14. Nc4 $2 {Now this would be a mistake, because Black can answer with} Ne5 $1 {∞ and in these structures if Black manages to exchange a pair of knights usually they are doing very well.}) 14... f5 {Black is consistent with their plan. Now we should remember by heart the following reaction.} (14... Ne5 $2 {doesn't make any sense because we can just play} 15. f4 {± and it's completely clear that Black went wrong as now their only move would be ...Nd7 back.}) 15. exf5 gxf5 16. f4 $1 {[%cal Rd7e5,Ge3c4,Ge2d3] Preventing Ne5, we will eventually play Nc4 on the next move, or maybe we will play Bd3 targeting Black's f5 pawn.} (16. Nc4 $2 Ne5 $1 {Again Black is in time to exchange our knight, as happened in the game Fedoseev-Matlakov 2012.}) 16... Ndf6 (16... Bd4 17. Kh1 Ndf6 18. Bd3 {±}) 17. Bd3 $1 {[%csl Rf5]} (17. Bd3 {It's not easy for Black to understand how to defend the f5 pawn. In the game Savchenko-Khanin 2019 Black played} Ne8 {but after many moves White is just better. For example, I like a useful move like Kh1 because maybe one day we will play Rg1 and g2-g3 trying to open the g line to mate Black's king.}) *

