1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} (3. f3 {The main continuations for Black are} d5 {(Grünfeld,) 3...Bg7 (King's Indian, and) 3...c5 (Benoni/King's Indian. In the first Chapter, we will explore Black's alternatives.)}) 3... c5 4. d5 e6 {As we will see in the 'Move Order Training', Black has many different move orders, but the final position at move nine will always be the same.} 5. e4 d6 {Black prevents e4-e5 ideas.} 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Nge2 {White's plan is to develop the knight to g3.} O-O 8. Ng3 exd5 9. cxd5 {This is the main position of the KID/Benoni variations.} a6 10. a4 h5 {Black's second most popular move. It is logical for Black to play against our knight on g3, since it may not have a lot of retreat squares.} 11. Be2 {We are not concerned about h5-h4 at this moment. Since we have not yet castled, our knight can retreat to f1. From f1, it can move to e3 and eventually reach the excellent c4 square.} (11. Bg5 {is another possible move, with the idea to stop h5-h4. We will speak about this move in a separate Chapter.}) 11... Nh7 (11... Nh7 {is a critical move in this position, likely the best option available for Black. It's an extremely useful move because it, first and foremost, prevents ideas involving Bg5. Additionally, it opens the diagonal for the bishop on g7 and clears the way for the f-pawn, enabling potential ideas related to f7-f5. ( Finally, it doesn't reveal Black's intentions too early, unlike the move 11...h4 , which we analyzed in the previous chapter. )}) 12. Nf1 $5 {Formally, this move isn't a novelty, as it was played once in 2015 by a German national master. However, given the current state of theory, we can safely say that it leads to completely new territory. White's idea is straightforward: we want to play Ne3 followed by Nc4. You may have noticed that this position is essentially the same as the one we analyzed in the previous chapter, with the key difference being that here Black hasn't committed to playing h5-h4. If Black does opt for h5-h4, we will transpose back to the previous chapter's lines. Instead, in this position, we need to explore the other alternatives available to Black.I also want to emphasize that the inclusion of the moves a6 and a4 is extremely important here: now Black has a weak square on b6. If the pawns were still on a2 and a7, this position would be less favorable for White. But the lines where Black plays without the inclusion of a6 and a4 will be the topic of our next chapter. For now, let's focus on this specific position.} (12. O-O $4 {This is a very famous mistake, after} Bd4+ 13. Kh1 h4 {-+ White's knight on g3 doesn't have any retreating square left.}) (12. Be3 {This is White's main line, and I've played many interesting games here, including against Karpov, Radjabov, Topalov, and several other strong grandmasters. While 12. Be3 is certainly an important direction, it has been deeply analyzed over the years, making it more challenging to find new ideas for White. Instead of following the well-trodden path, I want to present something fresh and, in my opinion, highly valuable.}) 12... f5 {Over the board, your opponent will need to make a decision on his own, and many players might proceed with f7-f5, even though the engine regards this move as questionable. In fact, in the only game where 12. Nf1 was played, Black did respond with 12...f5.} 13. Ne3 {We're proceeding with our standard plan. In my opinion, there is no need to include exf5.} f4 {This move is crucial from a strategic standpoint. Typically, Black is quite comfortable in this structure with the pawn on f4, especially if he can maneuver his knight from b8 to the e5 square. However, in this specific situation, the move 13... f4 doesn't work for Black ONLY due to concrete tactical reasons.} 14. Nc4 Qc7 {By playing this move Black wants to keep defended both the d6 pawn and the b6 square. He is now ready to continue with Nd7-Ne5.} (14... Nd7 $2 {It would be a great move. Black aims to continue with Ne5, which would immediately stabilize his position. However, in this case, his pawn on d6 is hanging! This detail might seem obvious, but it's the sole reason why 13...f4 doesn't work well for Black.}) (14... Qe7 {Black protects the d6 pawn, and is now ready to continue Nd7-Ne5. But also here there is a problem:} 15. Nb6 $1 {± .}) 15. g3 $16 (15. g3 {Black is not in time to maintain a strong pawn on f4. The issue is that fxg3 is very poor from a structural standpoint, and after} g5 {followed by} 16. gxf4 gxf4 {, the opening of the g file becomes extremely dangerous for Black due to the vulnerability of his king.}) *

