1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} (3. f3 {The main continuations for Black are} d5 {(Grünfeld,) 3...Bg7 (King's Indian, and) 3...c5 (Benoni/King's Indian. In the first Chapter, we will explore Black's alternatives.)}) 3... c5 4. d5 e6 {As we will see in the 'Move Order Training', Black has many different move orders, but the final position at move nine will always be the same.} 5. e4 d6 {Black prevents e4-e5 ideas.} 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Nge2 {White's plan is to develop the knight to g3.} O-O 8. Ng3 exd5 9. cxd5 {This is the main position of the KID/Benoni variations.} a6 10. a4 Nbd7 11. Be2 {In this chapter, we will take a look at the alternatives available for Black except the move 11...h5. There is not a lot of choice for Black, the only logical plan is to maneuver the knight to c7 where it can fight for the ...b7-b5 push, but it is a very time consuming plan.} Ne8 {This is an imprecise move order, in my opinion, because it allows us the extra option to play h4 as White's rook is still on h1.} 12. O-O ({For simplicity’s sake, I suggest} 12. O-O {, as the game is likely to transpose after} Rb8 {.}) 12... Nc7 {This is logical, but now our bishop develops with tempo.} 13. Bf4 Ne5 {This reply is double-edged. On one hand it does a good job at closing the h2-b8 diagonal, on the other it may come under f4 with tempo.} 14. Qd2 Rb8 15. Bg5 {Again, this typical reply. Now ...f6 is forced, otherwise f4 comes with tempo.} Qe8 {Now, White can just open up the position with f4!} 16. f4 $1 {[%cal Ge4e5] We are ready to meet ...Nd7 with e5!} Nd7 17. e5 $1 dxe5 18. f5 {[%cal Gd5d6,Gf5f6] Black's position is not defendable anymore.} f6 19. Be3 $18 {[%csl Gd5,Rg7][%cal Gd5d6] d6 comes next, and the engine suggests giving up a piece with ...Ne6 as Black's best strategy.} *

