1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} (3. f3 {The main continuations for Black are} d5 {(Grünfeld,) 3...Bg7 (King's Indian, and) 3...c5 (Benoni/King's Indian. In the first Chapter, we will explore Black's alternatives.)}) 3... c5 4. d5 e6 {As we will see in the 'Move Order Training', Black has many different move orders, but the final position at move nine will always be the same.} 5. e4 d6 {Black prevents e4-e5 ideas.} 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Nge2 {White's plan is to develop the knight to g3.} O-O 8. Ng3 exd5 9. cxd5 {This is the main position of the KID/Benoni variations.} a6 10. a4 Nbd7 11. Be2 {In this chapter, we will take a look at the alternatives available for Black except the move 11...h5. There is not a lot of choice for Black, the only logical plan is to maneuver the knight to c7 where it can fight for the ...b7-b5 push, but it is a very time consuming plan.} Rb8 {Black aims for the ...b7-b5 push and I believe this is the most precise move order.} 12. O-O Ne8 {The knight is being transfered to c7 and now it is time for White to decide.} 13. Re1 $5 {Out of the 125 games that reached this position, only 2 games continued this way, both of them were played by the current world champion Ding Liren against Ian Nepomniachtchi in 2019. The idea is very tricky, White waits for the knight to come to c7 so that Bf4 comes with tempo.} (13. Be3 {is the most played move, but Black can continue with} Nc7 {and now if we attack the pawn on d6 14.Bf4 we don't have Re1, which is a useful inclusion for White.}) (13. Bf4 {The immediate Bf4 is met with the strong} c4 $5 {And the b2 pawn is vulnerable, so Black has good counterplay after b7-b5.} 14. Bxc4 Qb6+ {And White needs to give up either the pawn or the exchange, where positions are complicated, but objectively playable for Black.}) 13... Nc7 {This is how the first game continued, now White developed with tempo.} 14. Bf4 Qe7 15. Qd2 Re8 (15... Re8 {So far, both sides are playing natural moves, here I think that} 16. Kh1 {is an improvement over what Ding played} (16. a5)) {. In the end, he won that game, so you can take a look if you are curious.} 16. Kh1 $5 {I believe we should allow ...b7-b5, under the circumstance that a-file will be completely at White's disposal.} (16. Bg5 {would be desired, but Black has the nice retreat to the f8 square.} Qf8 $1 {And Black is ready to push b7-b5.}) 16... b5 17. axb5 Nxb5 (17... axb5 $2 {This just blunders a pawn.} 18. Ra7 $1 {± And Black has to play either ...Rb7 or ...b4, in both cases losing a pawn.}) 18. Nxb5 {We capture again to open the a-file.} axb5 19. Ra5 $1 {A strong positional idea. White forces Black to push either ...b4 or c4 after which those pawn can be blockaded and the squares they weaken can be used by the pieces.} b4 {Logical, at least Black has no weak pawns, except d6.} (19... c4 20. Qb4 {⩲ Nicely blockades the pawns, sooner or later, the b5 pawn should fall.}) 20. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6,Gc6d7,Ga5a6] This is another annoying move for Black, stopping ...Ne5 and most likely Black will have to move again the rook on e8. It is a complex position, but White has the better chances.} *

