1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} (3. f3 {The main continuations for Black are} d5 {(Grünfeld,) 3...Bg7 (King's Indian, and) 3...c5 (Benoni/King's Indian. In the first Chapter, we will explore Black's alternatives.)}) 3... c5 4. d5 e6 {As we will see in the 'Move Order Training', Black has many different move orders, but the final position at move nine will always be the same.} 5. e4 d6 {Black prevents e4-e5 ideas.} 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Nge2 {White's plan is to develop the knight to g3.} O-O 8. Ng3 exd5 9. cxd5 {This is the main position of the KID/Benoni variations.} h5 {It might seem like we've seen this position before, but there’s actually a significant difference: the moves a6 and a4 have not been included. Recently, I’ve believed that this was the best way for Black to handle the position, as analysis often shows that including a6 and a4 tends to favor White.However, while preparing this course, I discovered an extraordinary idea that once again raises the question whether Black should start with 9...a6 or 9...h5.} 10. Bg5 {This move is important because it stops Black from playing ...Nh7 and ...h4.} Qb6 {This is Black’s most common continuation. It targets our b2 pawn while also unpinning the knight on f6.} 11. Qd2 Nh7 12. Bh4 $1 {This is a crucial move for White, and it works for tactical reasons.} (12. Be3 $6 {allows} h4 $1 {where our knight is forced to go back to e2, and we are not happy about it as we will need to spend some other time to develop our bishop from f1.}) 12... g5 {This move is objectively dubious, but it’s important for us to know it because we now need to sacrifice a piece.} (12... Nd7 13. Be2 {This transposes to a line that we will analyze in the next chapter.}) 13. Bxg5 Nxg5 14. Nxh5 $1 {We are now threatening Qxg5, where Qxb2 is impossible due to the mate on g7.} Nh7 {This is the only square available for retreating the knight.} 15. Nxg7 Kxg7 16. g4 $18 {[%cal Ge1c1,Ge4e5,Gf3f4,Gf4f5,Gg4g5,Gh2h4,Gh4h5] White's position is dominant. The plan is to castle long and then push all the pawns on the kingside h4-h5, g4-g5, f4-f5. Black's position is extremely difficult to play and is objectively lost.} *

