1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} (3. f3 {The main continuations for Black are} d5 {(Grünfeld,) 3...Bg7 (King's Indian, and) 3...c5 (Benoni/King's Indian. In the first Chapter, we will explore Black's alternatives.)}) 3... c5 4. d5 e6 {As we will see in the 'Move Order Training', Black has many different move orders, but the final position at move nine will always be the same.} 5. e4 d6 {Black prevents e4-e5 ideas.} 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Nge2 {White's plan is to develop the knight to g3.} O-O 8. Ng3 exd5 9. cxd5 {This is the main position of the KID/Benoni variations.} h5 {It might seem like we've seen this position before, but there’s actually a significant difference: the moves a6 and a4 have not been included. Recently, I’ve believed that this was the best way for Black to handle the position, as analysis often shows that including a6 and a4 tends to favor White.However, while preparing this course, I discovered an extraordinary idea that once again raises the question whether Black should start with 9...a6 or 9...h5.} 10. Bg5 {This move is important because it stops Black from playing ...Nh7 and ...h4.} a6 (10... a6 {10.Bg5 looks great so far, but what should we do after 10...a6? The issue is that if we play} 11. a4 {, we transpose into a line that we don't typically play because against 9...a6 followed by 10.a4 h5 , we opt for 11.Be2 , not 11.Bg5 . But don't worry, I’m not going to make you study another big line. I have a revolutionary idea here.}) (10... Nbd7 11. Be2 {This leads to a line that we’ll analyze in the next chapter.}) 11. Be2 $5 {We allow Black to play b7-b5. Normally, this isn’t advisable, but in this case, we can permit it because Black has already committed to h7-h5, which creates some weaknesses: Black's king is more exposed, and our bishop on g5 is more secure than it would be if the pawn were still on h7. This move completely overturns the usual logic of the variation. For many years, the common belief among strong grandmasters was that Black should start with 9...h5 without committing to the 9...a6 10. a4 inclusion, only opting for it when it was convenient.But now I want to propose that perhaps Black should actually start with the 9...a6 10. a4 inclusion, without committing to 9...h5, where after 10. Bg5 a6, we are no longer forced to prevent b7-b5 by playing 11. a4!} b5 {This is certainly Black's logical continuation. I'm sure your opponent will be surprised, but also quite pleased that you've allowed them to expand on the queenside with b7-b5. What they don't know yet is just how difficult the next few hours will be for them!} (11... Nbd7 12. a4 {Once again, this transposes into a line that we will analyze in the next chapter.}) 12. e5 {This move is a novelty. The push e4-e5 carries several positional ideas: after Black captures on e5, they will no longer have control over the crucial e5 square, which restricts the activity of his pieces. Additionally, White's pawn on d5 becomes a passed pawn, adding to the positional advantages.However, these general considerations alone don’t fully justify the pawn sacrifice with e4-e5. In this specific position, the key factor is that White's knight on c3 gains access to the critical e4 square. I also want to emphasize that Black's earlier move h7-h5 plays a decisive role here, as it ensures that White's bishop on g5 remains very stable.} (12. a4 $6 {Immediately would be a mistake because of} b4 {⩱ and our knight on c3 doesn't have a good square.}) 12... dxe5 13. a4 {If you check this position with an engine, you’ll notice that the evaluation remains at 0.00 after several of Black’s moves. However, as we’ll explore together, the lines suggested by the computer are far from natural for a human player. In fact, the more intuitive moves, such as 13...b4, lead to inferior positions for Black. This is why I strongly believe that the idea behind 12. e5 holds significant practical value. Even in the best lines available to Black—those recommended by the engine—you’ll see that the situation is not as simple for our opponent.This line is explained in more detail starting here.} *

