1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} (3. f3 {The main continuations for Black are} d5 {(Grünfeld,) 3...Bg7 (King's Indian, and) 3...c5 (Benoni/King's Indian. In the first Chapter, we will explore Black's alternatives.)}) 3... c5 4. d5 e6 {As we will see in the 'Move Order Training', Black has many different move orders, but the final position at move nine will always be the same.} 5. e4 d6 {Black prevents e4-e5 ideas.} 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Nge2 {White's plan is to develop the knight to g3.} O-O 8. Ng3 exd5 9. cxd5 {This is the main position of the KID/Benoni variations.} Nbd7 10. Be2 a6 11. a4 h5 12. Bg5 {Now, our bishop is well-placed on g5. Black needs to move the queen in order to have Nh7 ideas.} Qb6 {If Black wants to play with Qb6, then it's better for him to do it without the inclusion of the moves 10...a6 11. a4, because now, after Qd2, ...Nh7 is met by a5.} 13. Qd2 Nh7 14. a5 $1 {We are driving away the Black's queen from the b file, and this means that we will be able to continue with Bh6 on the next move because after Bxh6-Qxh6, our pawn on b2 will not hang.} Qc7 (14... Qb4 $2 {would allow} 15. Be7 {± .}) 15. Bh6 $14 {White has a very good version of the typical Saemisch positions that we are analyzing in this course. After the dark squared bishops exchange, Black's king will be weaker.} *

