1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} (3. f3 {The main continuations for Black are} d5 {(Grünfeld,) 3...Bg7 (King's Indian, and) 3...c5 (Benoni/King's Indian. In the first Chapter, we will explore Black's alternatives.)}) 3... c5 4. d5 e6 {As we will see in the 'Move Order Training', Black has many different move orders, but the final position at move nine will always be the same.} 5. e4 d6 {Black prevents e4-e5 ideas.} 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Nge2 {White's plan is to develop the knight to g3.} exd5 {This chapter explores a very serious and challenging variation available to Black, typically employed by top grandmasters rated over 2600. Due to its complexity, this chapter will be more intricate than usual, and I warn you in advance about the density of the material. The position we are analyzing is deeply complex, and simplifying it would fail to capture the necessary depth of analysis.However, players rated under 2400 should not be concerned, as it is highly unlikely that your opponents will steer into this variation, and even if they do, they are unlikely to have the expertise needed to successfully navigate these complications.} 8. cxd5 {In this chapter, we will analyze the variations where Black delays the short castle. These variations are critical from a theoretical point of view, and one of them was suggested by GM Anish Giri in his recent Lifetime Repertoires: Giri's Grünfeld.} a6 {This pawn push is always met with a2-a4, not allowing ...b7-b5. The problem with this move is that Black is committing to having a pawn on a6, which is not always good for them.} 9. a4 Nbd7 10. Ng3 h5 11. Be2 h4 12. Nf1 Rb8 $5 (12... Rb8 {This is a strong waiting and useful move for Black. It supports potential b7-b5 ideas, and it is a waiting move because if we play the standard} 13. Ne3 {, then} Nh5 {would be very strong for Black.}) (12... O-O 13. Bg5 $1 {transposes to another chapter.}) 13. a5 {We are not directly playing against b7-b5, as it wasn't an immediate threat, but we are making a useful move nonetheless.} (13. Bg5 {This is a logical move, but Black can respond with} h3 $1 {and their rook on h8 is useful: this is why they delayed the short castle.}) (13. Ne3 $6 Nh5 $1 {∓ Black is threatening Nf4, and we no longer have the g2-g4 idea, as was possible in the Nakamura-Kasparov game mentioned earlier.}) 13... O-O {Black doesn't have other useful moves and is already pleased to have provoked a4-a5, a move that White doesn't always need. Black is right, but now we rely on the following move.} 14. g4 $5 {[%cal Gf1e3] By playing this move, we are not only gaining space on the kingside but, more importantly, preventing Nh5 ideas, meaning we are now ready to proceed with Ne3.} ({Once again,} 14. Ne3 $6 {is a mistake because of} Nh5 $1 {where if you play a normal move like} 15. O-O {Black might already have} Ng3 $5 {ideas, because after} 16. hxg3 hxg3 {, it becomes difficult for us to defend against the 17...Qh4 threat.}) 14... b5 15. axb6 Nxb6 16. Bg5 $14 {[%csl Rh4]} (16. Bg5 {Black's pawn on h4 is a weakness, and if Black continues with} h3 {, then White can play} 17. Ne3 {, followed by castle.}) *

