1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} (3. f3 {The main continuations for Black are} d5 {(Grünfeld,) 3...Bg7 (King's Indian, and) 3...c5 (Benoni/King's Indian. In the first Chapter, we will explore Black's alternatives.)}) 3... c5 4. d5 e6 {As we will see in the 'Move Order Training', Black has many different move orders, but the final position at move nine will always be the same.} 5. e4 d6 {Black prevents e4-e5 ideas.} 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Nge2 {White's plan is to develop the knight to g3.} exd5 {This chapter explores a very serious and challenging variation available to Black, typically employed by top grandmasters rated over 2600. Due to its complexity, this chapter will be more intricate than usual, and I warn you in advance about the density of the material. The position we are analyzing is deeply complex, and simplifying it would fail to capture the necessary depth of analysis.However, players rated under 2400 should not be concerned, as it is highly unlikely that your opponents will steer into this variation, and even if they do, they are unlikely to have the expertise needed to successfully navigate these complications.} 8. cxd5 {In this chapter, we will analyze the variations where Black delays the short castle. These variations are critical from a theoretical point of view, and one of them was suggested by GM Anish Giri in his recent Lifetime Repertoires: Giri's Grünfeld.} Nbd7 {This is a very flexible move, because at the moment Black are not revealing any of their cards neither ...O-O or ...a6 were played.} 9. Ng3 h5 10. Be2 Nh7 {We have already encountered this position, except Black had included the move short castle instead of Nd7. More importantly, in that version, the moves a6-a4 had been played, but not in this case. We have already covered this topic in a full chapter.} 11. a4 $5 (11. a4 {I like this move for two reasons: First, we hope that Black will play} a6 {, which would allow us to play} 12. Nf1 $1 {because the moves a4-a6 have been included. However, it is likely Black will not play 11...a6 , and here comes the second reason: we will have the Ra1-Ra3 idea, which will be very important for concrete reasons, as we will see.}) 11... O-O 12. Ra3 {This is a very good waiting move for us: the rook will defend important squares on the third rank in some concrete lines.} Qe7 {This is an important move to check. Black is making a useful waiting move because after Nf1, they can play ...f5.} 13. Nf1 f5 {And now it's crucial to remember the following continuation.} 14. exf5 gxf5 15. Ng3 $14 (15. Ng3 {An important move. The idea is that in case of f5-f4, we can play Nge4, and the e4 square is great for our knight. In case of} h4 {, we can play} 16. Nh5 $1) (15. Ne3 $6 {is a standard move, but after} f4 {our knight must go to c4, where after} 16. Nc4 Ne5 $1 {Black is fine.}) *

