1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} (3. f3 {The main continuations for Black are} d5 {(Grünfeld,) 3...Bg7 (King's Indian, and) 3...c5 (Benoni/King's Indian. In the first Chapter, we will explore Black's alternatives.)}) 3... c5 4. d5 b5 $5 {We will now examine the Benko Gambit. However, this isn't a traditional Benko Gambit line. In the sequence 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.d5 b5 4.cxb5 a6 5.f3 , Black would never play 5...g6?! Instead, the typical and stronger move would be 5...axb5 . After 6.e4 , the main line continues with 6...Qa5+ , which is the most robust response. Therefore, rather than studying the entire f3 variation against the Benko Gambit, we will need to focus specifically on the most advantageous lines for White within this variation.} 5. cxb5 a6 {This is a classical continuation of the Benko gambit. Black sacrifices a pawn on the queenside but obtains some compensation in exchange thanks to the open a and b files.} 6. e4 d6 {It is needed against e4-e5 ideas, which would give White a huge space advantage.} 7. a4 $1 {We plan to develop the knight from b1 to a3 and the knight from g1 to c3. This setup will give us strong control over the b5 square, a key element in the Benko Gambit.} Bg7 8. Na3 O-O 9. Ne2 {We are now ready for Nc3.} e6 $1 ({Black's move} 9... e6 {is the strongest response, as it challenges the center before White can complete development.}) 10. Nc3 (10. dxe6 $5 {This move is also possible, but it leads to a non-standard play, where Black will also have their winning chances in a practical game.} fxe6 11. h4 $5 d5 $1 {∞ Objectively, White should be a bit better, but the position is very complicated and difficult to handle.}) 10... exd5 11. exd5 $1 ({The recapture} 11. exd5 $1 {is crucial. Although 9...exd5 slightly benefits Black by weakening the d5-pawn and opening the e-file, Black used a tempo with 9...e6 to reach this position. Therefore, Black must act quickly to generate effective counterplay.}) (11. Nxd5 $6 {This recapture is very natural, but now Black is fine:} Nxd5 12. Qxd5 Ra7 {The idea will be to continue with ...Be6 and d6-d5 next.}) 11... Nh5 $1 {[%csl Gg7][%cal Gd8h4] A very strong move. Black activates their bishop on g7, and at the same time threats Qh4+.} 12. g3 $1 {We have to play this move to prevent Qh4+.} Re8+ $2 {In all the four games that have reached this position, Black has played 12...Re8+, but this move helps White.} 13. Kf2 Bd4+ 14. Kg2 {[%csl Gg2][%cal Gf1c4,Gh1e1] White's King is very safe on g2. Now White can continue the development by playing Bc4-Re1, and Black can do little to stop it.} *

