1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 $5 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4. The move 3. f3 is part of the so-called 'Anti-Grünfeld' variations, which prevent Black from playing the Grünfeld in the typical fashion. However, the move 3...d5 is still possible against 3. f3, and it will be the focus of the first part of this course.} d5 (3... Nc6 {Black has several other minor options on move 3, with the most common being 3...Nc6. We will analyze all of them in Chapter 1.}) 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O (7... Nc6 {We will analyze 7...Nc6, along with other minor variations in Chapter 7.}) 8. Qd2 {This is the starting position of our Grünfeld Variation.} Nc6 (8... e5 9. d5 c6 {The most famous games in this variation are undoubtedly Anand-Gelfand in 2012, played in the third game of the World Championship match, and the 2016 Candidates Tournament game between Anish Giri and Fabiano Caruana. We will analyze it in Chapter 6.}) 9. O-O-O f5 (9... e5 {This used to be Black's old main line, but it is now considered dubious. We will analyze it in Chapter 2.}) (9... Qd6 {This move is often played at the highest levels, and we will analyze it in Chapter 5.}) 10. e5 f4 $5 {This revolutionary idea was first played by AlphaZero in its legendary match against Stockfish in 2017. I have decided to dedicate the entire Chapter 4 to this variation.} (10... Nb4 {This line is also very popular; we will analyze it in Chapter 3.}) *

