1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 (3. f3 {The main continuations for Black are} d5 {(Grünfeld,) 3...Bg7 (King's Indian, and) 3...c5 (Benoni/King's Indian. In the first Chapter, we will explore Black's alternatives.)}) 3... d6 4. Nc3 (4. Nc3 {Black can still play} Bg7 {, where after} 5. e4 {, we will transpose into the main King's Indian position.}) 4... e5 {This sideline has been played only twice, but in two high-level games: Wang vs. Nepomniachtchi in 2011 and Savchenko vs. Sindarov in 2024.} 5. Bg5 {[%cal Rd4e5] We are now threatening 6.dxe5 because after 6...dxe5 7.Qxd8 Kxd8 , Black's knight on f6 will be hanging.} (5. d5 $6 e4 $1 {∞ Black has good counterplay.}) 5... h6 $1 ({This is Black's best continuation.} 5... Bg7 $2 {Black had to include ...h6 and Bh4 before playing ...Bg7. Now White is winning on the spot:} 6. dxe5 dxe5 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Nd5 $1 {+- And if} Nbd7 {then} 9. O-O-O {with unstoppable threats.}) 6. Bh4 Bg7 7. dxe5 dxe5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {Because the moves ...h6-Bh4 were included, the move Nd5 is no longer winning, as Black can continue with g6-g5.} 9. O-O-O+ Nbd7 10. e3 $14 {[%cal Gf3f4,Gg1h3,Gh3f2,Gf2d3] White has the more favorable endgame. f3-f4 can be an idea, followed by developing our knight to f3. Alternatively, we can continue with Nh3-Nf2-Nd3.} *

