1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 (3. f3 {The main continuations for Black are} d5 {(Grünfeld,) 3...Bg7 (King's Indian, and) 3...c5 (Benoni/King's Indian. In the first Chapter, we will explore Black's alternatives.)}) 3... c6 $6 {Black's idea is to continue in the style of the symmetrical Grünfeld: playing ...d7-d5 and, in the event of cxd5, recapturing with the c-pawn. However, this approach doesn't work well against 3. f3, as White can follow up with e4.} 4. e4 d5 5. e5 $1 {White gains space while winning a tempo against the knight on f6. The move 3. f3 has been useful to support e2-e4, but now the pawn on f3 is slightly misplaced it would be much better on f2 or f4. However, this small detail doesn't compensate for all of Black's problems: lack of space, the knight getting kicked around, and ...g7-g6 giving us a hook for our attack later with h4-h5.} Nfd7 6. cxd5 {We don't want to give Black the opportunity to continue with ...dxc4, when the knight on d7 could suddenly be maneuvered to the excellent square on d5.} cxd5 (6... Nb6 {then after} 7. dxc6 Nxc6 8. Bb5 Bg7 9. Ne2 O-O 10. O-O {± It is clear that Black doesn't have enough compensation for the missing pawn.}) 7. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5] White wants to continue with h4-h5.} h5 8. Bd3 $16 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gg1e2,Gb1c3,Gc1g5,Ge1h1] Because the moves h4 and ...h5 have been included, it will now be much more difficult for Black to play the typical ...f7-f6, due to the vulnerability of the g6-pawn. White, on the other hand, can continue with standard moves like Nge2, Nbc3, O-O, and Bg5, enjoying the space advantage and more active pieces at no cost.} *

