1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 (3. f3 {The main continuations for Black are} d5 {(Grünfeld,) 3...Bg7 (King's Indian, and) 3...c5 (Benoni/King's Indian. In the first Chapter, we will explore Black's alternatives.)}) 3... e6 {Black's idea is to continue with ...d7-d5, and if cxd5, they can recapture with the e pawn.} 4. e4 d5 {5...c5 5.d5 d6 6.Nc3 Bg7 7.Nge2 exd5 8.cxd5 O-O This one will be our main position of the KID/Benoni variation. We will analyze it in great detail in the third part of this course.} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Nc3 $1 (6. e5 $6 Nfd7 {∞ If we compare this position to the one arising from the 3...c6 variation, here Black has a pawn on c7 instead of e7. This allows them to create good counterplay by playing c7-c5.}) 6... dxe4 7. fxe4 {White has a strong center, and Black needs to be very quick in creating counterplay, or else they will find themselves in a much worse position.} Bg7 $6 {This normal move fails to create adequate counterplay.} 8. Nf3 O-O 9. e5 ({But not} 9. Bd3 $6 Bg4 {∞}) 9... Nd5 10. Bc4 Be6 11. Qb3 $16 {[%csl Rd5,Rb7]} (11. Qb3 {We’re targeting both the knight on d5 and the pawn on b7. Black’s only response is} c6 {, but after} 12. Qxb7 {, we’ll simply reach a position with an extra pawn.}) *

