1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 (3. f3 {The main continuations for Black are} d5 {(Grünfeld,) 3...Bg7 (King's Indian, and) 3...c5 (Benoni/King's Indian. In the first Chapter, we will explore Black's alternatives.)}) 3... e6 {Black's idea is to continue with ...d7-d5, and if cxd5, they can recapture with the e pawn.} 4. e4 d5 {5...c5 5.d5 d6 6.Nc3 Bg7 7.Nge2 exd5 8.cxd5 O-O This one will be our main position of the KID/Benoni variation. We will analyze it in great detail in the third part of this course.} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Nc3 $1 (6. e5 $6 Nfd7 {∞ If we compare this position to the one arising from the 3...c6 variation, here Black has a pawn on c7 instead of e7. This allows them to create good counterplay by playing c7-c5.}) 6... dxe4 7. fxe4 {White has a strong center, and Black needs to be very quick in creating counterplay, or else they will find themselves in a much worse position.} Bb4 $1 {Black is now threatening ...Nxe4. Their position would have been great, were it not for the move ...g7-g6, which has left many dark squares on the kingside unprotected.} 8. Bg5 $1 {White's critical continuation, in my opinion.} h6 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. Nf3 Bg4 $1 {[%cal Gb8c6] Black's idea is to pressure our d4-pawn by continuing with Nc6.} (10... O-O $6 {is too slow.} 11. Bc4 {± White will continue with short castle and has a huge initiative.}) 11. Bb5+ $3 {A critical move. We force c7-c6, and only then do we retreat our bishop to e2. By doing this, we ensure that Black won't be able to develop their knight to c6.} (11. Be2 Nc6 $1 {⩱ or 11.Bc4 Nc6! ∞}) 11... c6 (11... Nc6 $2 {doesn't make any sense now that our bishop is on b5.} 12. O-O O-O-O 13. Nd5 {±}) 12. Be2 $14 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gd1c2,Ga2a3,Ga1d1] White has successfully maintained their strong center. We can continue with short castling, Qc2-Rad1, and eventually a plan like a3-b4 possibly even b4-b5 later on. While Black's position is far from lost, it's clear that they haven't managed to equalize out of the opening.} *

