1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 (3. f3 {The main continuations for Black are} d5 {(Grünfeld,) 3...Bg7 (King's Indian, and) 3...c5 (Benoni/King's Indian. In the first Chapter, we will explore Black's alternatives.)}) 3... Nc6 (3... Nc6 {This is Black's most common sideline. The idea is to respond to} 4. e4 {with} e5 {.}) ({The obvious drawback of the move} 3... Nc6 {is that after} 4. d5 {, the knight will have to waste tempi finding a safe square. On the other hand, Black hopes to gain something from provoking the d4-d5 push; often, they will try to challenge our pawn on d5 by playing c7-c6 or e7-e6.}) 4. d5 Ne5 5. e4 {[%cal Gf3f4]} d6 {White was threatening f3-f4, so Black had to create an escape square on d7 for their knight on e5.} 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. f4 Ned7 8. Nh3 $1 {[%cal Gh3f2] A very important move. Since we have played the ambitious f3-f4, we must be aware that our pawn on e4 could become vulnerable in the near future. By playing 8. Nh3, we can maneuver our knight to f2, where it will securely defend the e4 pawn. I want to point out that Nh3 should be played immediately because, for the moment, Black's knight is on d7. If we delay Nh3 in favor of another development move, Black could play ...Nc5, making Nh3 impossible due to ...Bxh3.} O-O 9. Nf2 Nc5 10. Be2 {Both sides have made their desired developing moves, and it's difficult to imagine any other significant deviations. But now Black must decide whether to continue with c7-c6 or e7-e6.} (10. Be2 {I want to point out, for practical purposes, how it makes no difference whether Black plays} e5 {or 10...e6 because in both cases, we will continue with 11.dxe6 .}) 10... c6 {This move is much less common compared to 10...e6, but it was played in 2018 by the expert Grünfeld player Peter Svidler.} 11. Be3 $1 {White's most precise move order and it is intended against the ...cxd5-cxd5-...b5! idea.} (11. dxc6 $6 {(If against 10...e6 or 10...e5 our reaction will be 11. dxe6, here the capture turns out to be a serious positional mistake because by recapturing with)} bxc6 {∞ , Black gains strong control of the center.}) (11. O-O $6 {would be an inaccuracy because Black can continue with} cxd5 12. cxd5 b5 $1 {∞ when} 13. Bxb5 {fails due to all the captures on e4 followed by ...Qb6+ regaining the bishop.}) 11... cxd5 12. cxd5 $1 (12. exd5 $6 e6 13. dxe6 Bxe6 {∞ In this position, White would be better if the pawn were on e4 instead of c4.}) 12... e6 $6 (12... b5 $2 {This was good against 11. O-O, but here it is bad because of} 13. Bxc5 dxc5 14. e5 Nd7 15. Bxb5 {±}) 13. dxe6 Bxe6 14. O-O $16 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ga1c1,Gf1d1] White can continue with simple moves like Qd2-Rac1-Rfd1.} *

