1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} d5 {Black has several other minor options on move 3, with the most common being 3...Nc6. We analyze all of them in Chapter 1.} 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 {This is the starting position of our Grünfeld Variation.} Nc6 9. O-O-O e5 {This used to be the main line. On one hand, the continuation ...e5 d5 ...Nd4 was considered a standard and natural sequence before the advent of computers. Today, it is well known that Black cannot resolve their opening issues. Consequently, this line has been gradually abandoned in favor of other approaches which we will explore in the following chapters.} 10. d5 Ne7 $2 {This is too passive.} 11. h4 $16 {[%cal Gh4h5] White has a strategically won position. We can continue with h4-h5, and if Black plays ...h5 themselves, then g2-g4 becomes a typical idea.} *

