1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} d5 {Black has several other minor options on move 3, with the most common being 3...Nc6. We analyze all of them in Chapter 1.} 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 {This is the starting position of our Grünfeld Variation.} Nc6 9. O-O-O e5 {This used to be the main line. On one hand, the continuation ...e5 d5 ...Nd4 was considered a standard and natural sequence before the advent of computers. Today, it is well known that Black cannot resolve their opening issues. Consequently, this line has been gradually abandoned in favor of other approaches which we will explore in the following chapters.} 10. d5 Nd4 {[%cal Gc7c6] This is the starting position of the 9...e5 line. Black's idea is to play c7-c6, challenging our center. It's extremely important to not allow them time to do it.} 11. f4 $1 {[%csl Rd4] We are challenging the stability of Black's knight on d4.} Bg4 {This developing move gains a tempo against our rook on d1 and prevents Nf3 ideas.} 12. Re1 c5 {Understanding that the pawn on e5 won't provide sufficient stability for the knight on d4, Black has no choice but to support it with the c-pawn.} 13. fxe5 Bxe5 14. h3 $1 {As soon as Black's bishop leaves the d1-h5 diagonal, we can proceed with Nf3!} Qh4 {This move was very popular in the 1990s and 2000s. By exploiting the pin on the h-pawn, Black aims to keep the bishop on the d1-h5 diagonal, preventing our planned move Nf3. However, this approach seems overly artificial, and modern computers easily find an advantage for White.} 15. Bd3 {This isn't White's only good move, but it seems the simplest. We develop a piece while further supporting our pawn on e4.} Rac8 {This move doesn't pose any significant threats, but it's certainly useful and by far the most played move by Black.} 16. Rf1 $5 {We improve our rook. White has many useful moves available, while Black lacks a good plan. As soon as Black plays ...Bd7, Nf3! becomes a strong option for us. For this reason, in almost all games, Black has tried the concrete move ...f5.} f5 17. hxg4 $1 {Once again, we will sacrifice the exchange to achieve tremendous activity for our pieces. Please note that we play hxg4 only after Black has played f7-f5, because this way, after Black captures the rook on h1, we can continue by capturing the pawn on f5.} Qxh1 18. Nh3 Qh2 19. gxf5 $16 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Ge3f4,Re5f4,Gf4e6,Gh3g5,Gg5e6] Our plan is to bring a knight to e6. It is not clear how Black will create counterplay.} *

