1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} d5 {Black has several other minor options on move 3, with the most common being 3...Nc6. We analyze all of them in Chapter 1.} 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 {This is the starting position of our Grünfeld Variation.} Nc6 9. O-O-O f5 {In this chapter, we will examine 9...f5, which is Black's most common move. Black has a cunning plan in mind: ...fxe4 followed by fxe4 and then ...Nxd4! The danger lies in the fact that after the exchanges on d4, our bishop on f1 will be left unprotected.} 10. e5 {This is the most principled continuation for White. Now, Black's bishop is temporarily out of play, blocked by our pawns on d4 and e5, but Black has gained control of the important d5 square for their pieces. White's typical plan will be to continue with h4-h5, aiming to launch a quick attack on the kingside.} (10. h4 $5 {An interesting and very aggressive move. Black must be well-prepared for the correct follow-up, but if so, it will be difficult for White to gain an advantage.} fxe4 11. h5 gxh5 $1 {Black's best continuation.} 12. Rxh5 Bf5 13. Rg5 $5 {We are threatening Rxg7+, but after} Bg6 {I couldn't find anything satisfactory for White to fight for an advantage.}) 10... Nb4 {This is by far the most frequently played move by Black, and it aligns perfectly with the strategy of playing for control of the d5 square.} (10... Be6 $4 {That would be a serious mistake due to} 11. d5 $1 {+- .}) 11. Nh3 $1 {Our knight is looking for the g5- or f4-squares, depending on the situation.} N6d5 $2 {[%cal Rb6c4,Gf1c4] Even though it may seem natural, placing a knight on d5 is not a good strategy for Black. However, if Black insists on doing so, it's certainly better in this case to move the knight from b4, allowing the knight on b6 to control the important c4-square.} 12. Bc4 $16 {White has a significant advantage and is in a winning position according to the engine. The bishop on c4 is very strong, and Black cannot counter it by playing ...Be6 due to the threat of Ng5.} e6 (12... Be6 13. Ng5 $1 {+- Black was not in time to stabilize the bishop on e6.}) 13. Nf4 {We add maximum pressure on d5.} c6 14. Bxd5 cxd5 15. h4 $18 {[%csl Rg8] Black's pieces are very passive, and the king is in danger. The position is closed, so the pair of bishops is not relevant. White is winning.} *

