1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} d5 {Black has several other minor options on move 3, with the most common being 3...Nc6. We analyze all of them in Chapter 1.} 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 {This is the starting position of our Grünfeld Variation.} Nc6 9. O-O-O f5 {In this chapter, we will examine 9...f5, which is Black's most common move. Black has a cunning plan in mind: ...fxe4 followed by fxe4 and then ...Nxd4! The danger lies in the fact that after the exchanges on d4, our bishop on f1 will be left unprotected.} 10. e5 {This is the most principled continuation for White. Now, Black's bishop is temporarily out of play, blocked by our pawns on d4 and e5, but Black has gained control of the important d5 square for their pieces. White's typical plan will be to continue with h4-h5, aiming to launch a quick attack on the kingside.} (10. h4 $5 {An interesting and very aggressive move. Black must be well-prepared for the correct follow-up, but if so, it will be difficult for White to gain an advantage.} fxe4 11. h5 gxh5 $1 {Black's best continuation.} 12. Rxh5 Bf5 13. Rg5 $5 {We are threatening Rxg7+, but after} Bg6 {I couldn't find anything satisfactory for White to fight for an advantage.}) 10... Nb4 {This is by far the most frequently played move by Black, and it aligns perfectly with the strategy of playing for control of the d5 square.} (10... Be6 $4 {That would be a serious mistake due to} 11. d5 $1 {+- .}) 11. Nh3 $1 {Our knight is looking for the g5- or f4-squares, depending on the situation.} a5 {This is a typical move that Black plays sooner or later because it supports the knight on b4 and aims to create some counterplay on the queenside. The question is whether 11...a5 is so essential that it needs to be played immediately instead of other developing moves. As we will see shortly, 11...a5 is indeed a bit premature.} 12. a3 $1 N4d5 13. Nf4 $1 {Once again, Nf4 is the correct continuation. If you think about it, it's the same position we saw in the 11...N4d5 variation, but with the difference that the pawns are now on a3 and a5. This detail might slightly favor Black, but it's still not enough to guarantee equality.} Nxf4 14. Bxf4 Nd5 15. Bc4 $1 {[%csl Rd5] White puts pressure on the important a2-g8 diagonal, and it's not easy for Black to unpin the knight.} Be6 (15... e6 $2 {would be a serious positional mistake.} 16. Bxd5 exd5 17. h4 {+- White's center is solid, Black's bishops are inactive, Black has no queenside attack and no counterplay. White's position is already winning.}) (15... c6 $6 {is followed by} 16. h4 {± when White again exerts strong pressure on the d5 square, and will proceed with h4-h5 or, in some cases, exchange with Bxd5 followed by cxd5 and h4-h5.}) 16. Bg5 Qd7 {And now, after the exchange of all the pieces on d5, we will reach a typical advantageous position for White.} 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 18. Bxd5+ Qxd5 19. Kb1 $14 {[%csl Gg5,Rg7][%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5,Rc7c5] We reach a typical advantageous position for White. The plan of h4-h5 is always available, and the difference between the bishops is evident: Black's bishop is blocked by our pawns on d4 and e5, and having played f7-f5 doesn't help, as they no longer have the option to play f7-f6 to challenge our center. The only plan for Black is to organize c7-c5, but even if successful, it would at best allow Black to reach a slightly unfavorable endgame.} *

