1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} d5 {Black has several other minor options on move 3, with the most common being 3...Nc6. We analyze all of them in Chapter 1.} 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 {This is the starting position of our Grünfeld Variation.} Nc6 9. O-O-O f5 {In this chapter, we will examine 9...f5, which is Black's most common move. Black has a cunning plan in mind: ...fxe4 followed by fxe4 and then ...Nxd4! The danger lies in the fact that after the exchanges on d4, our bishop on f1 will be left unprotected.} 10. e5 {This is the most principled continuation for White. Now, Black's bishop is temporarily out of play, blocked by our pawns on d4 and e5, but Black has gained control of the important d5 square for their pieces. White's typical plan will be to continue with h4-h5, aiming to launch a quick attack on the kingside.} (10. h4 $5 {An interesting and very aggressive move. Black must be well-prepared for the correct follow-up, but if so, it will be difficult for White to gain an advantage.} fxe4 11. h5 gxh5 $1 {Black's best continuation.} 12. Rxh5 Bf5 13. Rg5 $5 {We are threatening Rxg7+, but after} Bg6 {I couldn't find anything satisfactory for White to fight for an advantage.}) 10... Nb4 {This is by far the most frequently played move by Black, and it aligns perfectly with the strategy of playing for control of the d5 square.} (10... Be6 $4 {That would be a serious mistake due to} 11. d5 $1 {+- .}) 11. Nh3 $1 {Our knight is looking for the g5- or f4-squares, depending on the situation.} Qe8 {This move doesn't hold much theoretical value, but I wanted to show you a game played by Carlsen in 2015.} 12. Kb1 {It's not the only good move for White, but it's an excellent prophylactic move, certainly useful for improving the position. Also, 12. Nf4 could have been considered.} a5 {Black supports his knight on b4 and tries to create counterplay on the queenside.} 13. Be2 (13. Rc1 $5 {± Rc1 is a move that the engine likes a lot because our rook is very useful on the c file. If you think about it, it's also the logical continuation of 12. Kb1. However, the move played by Carlsen, though slower, is equally good.}) 13... c6 14. Rc1 {Now Carlsen plays it.} Kh8 {A logical move played by Li Chao. Black aims to continue with ...Be6, so that after Nf4, the bishop will be able to retreat to the g8 square.} (14... Be6 {This is not great for Black, because after Nf4 ...Bf7 won't be possible due to e6! trapping the bishop. This is where one of the drawbacks of the move ...Qe8 becomes evident.} 15. Nf4 {±}) 15. Ka1 {Carlsen continues to handle the position with extreme calm, taking the time to play another prophylactic move. We certainly have much to learn from moves like this.} (15. a3 $5 {This is White's best continuation, according to the engines.} N4d5 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. Nf4 {±}) 15... Be6 16. Nf4 Qf7 {Now the game is about to become very complicated. Let’s follow the developments for a few more moves.} (16... Bg8 {This would have been the logical continuation, but White would have had an excellent initiative after} 17. h4 {.}) (16... Bc4 {Na4! +-}) 17. h4 Bxa2 {This is certainly a challenging move, but it’s losing for concrete reasons.} (17... Rfd8 $1 {is Black's best defense, according to the engine.}) 18. h5 Kg8 (18... g5 19. Ng6+ $1 {±}) 19. hxg6 hxg6 20. g4 $1 Bb3 {And now, I really liked the final finesse.} 21. Bd1 $18 {[%cal Gd2h2] Qh2 is coming, and Black's position is simply lost. This was the case in the Carlsen-Li Chao game in 2015.} *

