what happens if Black decides to immediately utilize the c4-square for one of his pieces.} 13. Bxc4 $1 Bxc4 14. b3 $1 {Black has managed to obtain the bishop pair, but now it will be much more difficult for them to create counterplay on the queenside. Meanwhile, as we'll see in this exemplary game, White can execute his plans much more swiftly.} Bf7 (14... Bd3+ {is a pointless check and leaves both the knight and bishop in trouble with a2-a3 coming soon.}) 15. Bh6 {We already know that Black's bishop is passive; however, when the dynamic circumstances are favorable, we can also consider exchanging the bishops to weaken Black's king, thereby creating a quick kingside attack.} Nd5 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 18. Nf4 $16 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5] White will continue with h4-h5, making Black's position very difficult. This was the case in the Shankland-Ftacnik game in 2013, where White won convincingly.} *

