1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} d5 {Black has several other minor options on move 3, with the most common being 3...Nc6. We analyze all of them in Chapter 1.} 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 {This is the starting position of our Grünfeld Variation.} Nc6 9. O-O-O f5 {In this chapter, we will examine 9...f5, which is Black's most common move. Black has a cunning plan in mind: ...fxe4 followed by fxe4 and then ...Nxd4! The danger lies in the fact that after the exchanges on d4, our bishop on f1 will be left unprotected.} 10. e5 {This is the most principled continuation for White. Now, Black's bishop is temporarily out of play, blocked by our pawns on d4 and e5, but Black has gained control of the important d5 square for their pieces. White's typical plan will be to continue with h4-h5, aiming to launch a quick attack on the kingside.} (10. h4 $5 {An interesting and very aggressive move. Black must be well-prepared for the correct follow-up, but if so, it will be difficult for White to gain an advantage.} fxe4 11. h5 gxh5 $1 {Black's best continuation.} 12. Rxh5 Bf5 13. Rg5 $5 {We are threatening Rxg7+, but after} Bg6 {I couldn't find anything satisfactory for White to fight for an advantage.}) 10... Nb4 {This is by far the most frequently played move by Black, and it aligns perfectly with the strategy of playing for control of the d5 square.} (10... Be6 $4 {That would be a serious mistake due to} 11. d5 $1 {+- .}) 11. Nh3 $1 {Our knight is looking for the g5- or f4-squares, depending on the situation.} Be6 {This is the most played move and also the most logical one available to Black, as it develops a piece while simultaneously gaining control of the important d5-square.} 12. Kb1 {We have already learned from the Carlsen-Li Chao game the importance of Kb1! as a prophylactic move.} Qd7 {The most played move, and also the best for Black. It is certainly a useful move, with one idea being to play ...Na4, aiming to create counterplay on the queenside.} 13. Nf4 $1 {Now, Black has two important theoretical options: 13... Bf7 and 13... Rfd8.} (13. Ng5 $6 {It might seem more logical than 13. Nf4, but it doesn't work due to concrete reasons:} Nc4 $1 14. Qc1 Nxe3 15. Qxe3 Bh6 $1 {∞ In 13. Nf4, we will see the same position but with our knight on f4. This changes everything because we will then have the opportunity to play 16. d5!, which is not possible in the current position.}) 13... Nc4 $6 {This move was good against 13. Ng5, but here it doesn’t work} 14. Qc1 Nxe3 15. Qxe3 c6 {It was played in a very instructive game, Vidit-Maghsodloo 2016.} 16. Nxe6 Qxe6 17. a3 Nd5 18. Nxd5 $1 cxd5 (18... Qxd5 {is also possible, but White will manage to develop the bishop on c4.} 19. Rc1 Kh8 20. Bc4 Qd7 21. h4 {± Black's king is in danger. If Black plays} h5 {, then White will have g2-g4 ideas in the future.}) 19. h4 $16 {Black is likely already in a lost position. The bishop on g7 is extremely passive, and White has the simple plan of launching an attack on the kingside. At the same time, Black has no chances for counterplay on the queenside.} *

