so the best for Black. It is certainly a useful move, with one idea being to play ...Na4, aiming to create counterplay on the queenside.} 13. Nf4 $1 {Now, Black has two important theoretical options: 13... Bf7 and 13... Rfd8.} (13. Ng5 $6 {It might seem more logical than 13. Nf4, but it doesn't work due to concrete reasons:} Nc4 $1 14. Qc1 Nxe3 15. Qxe3 Bh6 $1 {∞ In 13. Nf4, we will see the same position but with our knight on f4. This changes everything because we will then have the opportunity to play 16. d5!, which is not possible in the current position.}) 13... Nc4 $6 {This move was good against 13. Ng5, but here it doesn’t work} 14. Qc1 Nxe3 15. Qxe3 Bh6 {This was the strongest continuation in the 13. Ng5 variation.} 16. d5 $1 {Entering a forced line.} Nxd5 17. Ncxd5 Bxd5 18. Rxd5 Qxd5 (18... Bxf4 $4 19. Qxf4 $1 Qxd5 20. Bc4 {+-}) 19. Nxd5 Bxe3 20. Nxe3 $16 {White is simply winning.} *

