so the best for Black. It is certainly a useful move, with one idea being to play ...Na4, aiming to create counterplay on the queenside.} 13. Nf4 $1 {Now, Black has two important theoretical options: 13... Bf7 and 13... Rfd8.} (13. Ng5 $6 {It might seem more logical than 13. Nf4, but it doesn't work due to concrete reasons:} Nc4 $1 14. Qc1 Nxe3 15. Qxe3 Bh6 $1 {∞ In 13. Nf4, we will see the same position but with our knight on f4. This changes everything because we will then have the opportunity to play 16. d5!, which is not possible in the current position.}) 13... Bf7 {An ambitious move, as Black tries to preserve the light-squared bishop. However, this move costs a tempo, and it's by no means certain that Black will be able to equalize, as we will see.} 14. a3 $1 a5 $6 {[%csl Rb6] Black's idea is to attack along the a-file in case we capture the knight. We will not take on b4, which would indeed allow strong counterplay, but instead we will focus on the slightly weakened position of the black knight on b6.} 15. Bb5 $1 c6 16. d5 $1 {[%cal Ge3b6] Now you can see what I was talking about: due to the move 14... a5, the knight on b6 is now undefended.} cxb5 (16... Bxe5 17. Bxb6 cxb5 18. Rhe1 {leads to the same.}) 17. Bxb6 Bxe5 18. Rhe1 Bf6 19. Bd4 $18 {White has a decisive advantage due to the dominant position of all their pieces.} *

