so the best for Black. It is certainly a useful move, with one idea being to play ...Na4, aiming to create counterplay on the queenside.} 13. Nf4 $1 {Now, Black has two important theoretical options: 13... Bf7 and 13... Rfd8.} (13. Ng5 $6 {It might seem more logical than 13. Nf4, but it doesn't work due to concrete reasons:} Nc4 $1 14. Qc1 Nxe3 15. Qxe3 Bh6 $1 {∞ In 13. Nf4, we will see the same position but with our knight on f4. This changes everything because we will then have the opportunity to play 16. d5!, which is not possible in the current position.}) 13... Bf7 {An ambitious move, as Black tries to preserve the light-squared bishop. However, this move costs a tempo, and it's by no means certain that Black will be able to equalize, as we will see.} 14. a3 $1 N4d5 15. Ncxd5 Nxd5 16. Bc4 $1 {Once again, when White manages to develop his bishop to c4, He gains a significant positional advantage.} Nxf4 17. Bxf7+ Rxf7 18. Bxf4 $14 {We have already seen a similar position. Let me repeat the comment that I gave you on that occasion. We reach a typical advantageous position for White. The plan of h4-h5 is always available, and the difference between the bishops is evident: Black's bishop is blocked by our pawns on d4 and e5, and the fact that they have played f7-f5 doesn't help, as he no longer has the option to play f7-f6. The only plan for Black in this position is to try to organize c7-c5, but even if successful, it would at best allow them to reach a slightly unfavorable endgame.} *

