so the best for Black. It is certainly a useful move, with one idea being to play ...Na4, aiming to create counterplay on the queenside.} 13. Nf4 $1 {Now, Black has two important theoretical options: 13... Bf7 and 13... Rfd8.} (13. Ng5 $6 {It might seem more logical than 13. Nf4, but it doesn't work due to concrete reasons:} Nc4 $1 14. Qc1 Nxe3 15. Qxe3 Bh6 $1 {∞ In 13. Nf4, we will see the same position but with our knight on f4. This changes everything because we will then have the opportunity to play 16. d5!, which is not possible in the current position.}) 13... Rfd8 {This move has been played in slightly fewer games than 13... Bf7, but I believe it is the best continuation for Black.} 14. a3 N4d5 $6 {This move is poor from a strategic standpoint.} 15. Ncxd5 Bxd5 (15... Nxd5 16. Nxe6 Qxe6 17. Bc4 {±}) 16. Nxd5 Qxd5 {[%cal Gc7c5] Now Black's idea is c7-c5, which is why I really like the prophylactic move that follows.} 17. Qc1 $1 (17. Qc1 {The point is that after} c5 {, we can play} 18. dxc5 $1 {since} Qxd1 {is not possible due to} 19. Bc4+ Nxc4 20. Rxd1 Rxd1 21. Qxd1 Nxe3 {when} 22. Qb3+ $1 {picks off the knight with a clean win.}) (17. h4 c5 $1 {It was played in the game Svetushkin-Stella in 2013, and Black quickly achieved an excellent position.}) 17... Rac8 18. h4 $16 {[%cal Gh4h5,Gf1e2,Gd1d2,Gh1d1] White is simply better and can continue with their typical h4-h5 idea. If you want to play more solidly, you can continue with Be2-Rd2-Rhd1.} *

