so the best for Black. It is certainly a useful move, with one idea being to play ...Na4, aiming to create counterplay on the queenside.} 13. Nf4 $1 {Now, Black has two important theoretical options: 13... Bf7 and 13... Rfd8.} (13. Ng5 $6 {It might seem more logical than 13. Nf4, but it doesn't work due to concrete reasons:} Nc4 $1 14. Qc1 Nxe3 15. Qxe3 Bh6 $1 {∞ In 13. Nf4, we will see the same position but with our knight on f4. This changes everything because we will then have the opportunity to play 16. d5!, which is not possible in the current position.}) 13... Rfd8 {This move has been played in slightly fewer games than 13... Bf7, but I believe it is the best continuation for Black.} 14. a3 a5 $1 15. d5 $1 {White's critical continuation. We are temporarily sacrificing a pawn, but Black will not be able to stabilize without incurring greater material losses due to the multiple pins.} (15. Bb5 $2 {Now this idea is not as good as after 13... Bf7, because after} c6 16. d5 {Black can play} N6xd5 $1 {as after} 17. axb4 Nxf4 $1 {-+ the queen on d7 is defended twice.}) 15... N4xd5 16. Ncxd5 Nxd5 17. Bc4 c6 {Black's only move.} 18. Bb6 $1 {Exploiting the pins.} Rdc8 $2 {A very natural move that has been often played, but is a huge positional mistake.} (18... Nxb6 $4 19. Bxe6+ Qxe6 20. Qxd8+ Rxd8 21. Rxd8+ Kf7 22. Nxe6 {+-}) 19. Nxe6 Qxe6 20. f4 $16 {[%csl Rd5,Rg7] White will continue with 21.Bxd5 cxd5 22.Qxd5 Qxd5 23.Rxd5 , entering a clearly superior endgame due to the passive bishop on g7.} *

