1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} d5 {Black has several other minor options on move 3, with the most common being 3...Nc6. We analyze all of them in Chapter 1.} 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 {This is the starting position of our Grünfeld Variation.} Nc6 9. O-O-O f5 10. e5 f4 $5 {This move was first played in the 2018 Stockfish vs. AlphaZero match. It involves a pawn sacrifice that offers long-term compensation, something too deep to be fully grasped by any human or computer until that point. The first player to use this move in a practical game was the Grünfeld expert GM Emil Sutovsky, who played it a few months later in 2018.} 11. Bxf4 Nb4 {The move that was played by AlphaZero in the aforementioned game.} 12. a3 {Stockfish plays the most critical move in the position. This choice demonstrates the engine's precise calculation and deep understanding of the position, challenging AlphaZero's strategy and testing the depth of its long-term compensation. The game exemplifies the high level of play and the intense competition between these two advanced chess engines, where each move is a blend of tactical sharpness and strategic foresight.} N4d5 {This is the normal response of a human player, but White actually gains an advantage. It's clear that AlphaZero had an entirely different plan in mind.} 13. Bg5 $1 Nxc3 14. Qxc3 Qd5 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gc7c5] Black is ready to play ...Be6, followed by c7-c5, creating strong counterplay on the light squares.} 15. Ne2 $1 {[%cal Ge2f4] Preparing Nf4 ideas.} Qa2 16. Kd2 $16 {[%cal Gd2e1] This is a very strong move if Black plays ...Qa2. The idea is to reposition the king to e1, where it will be perfectly safe. At this point, Black no longer has sufficient compensation for the missing pawn.} (16. Kd2 {After} Nd5 17. Qc1 $1 {It's important to keep b2 covered while avoiding 17.Qc2? Bf5 tempo hit.}) *

