1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} d5 {Black has several other minor options on move 3, with the most common being 3...Nc6. We analyze all of them in Chapter 1.} 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 {This is the starting position of our Grünfeld Variation.} Nc6 9. O-O-O Qd6 ({Unlike the historically well-known moves} 9... e5 {and 9...f5 , this move is relatively new to chess theory. It was first played in the game Mamedyarov-Petrosian Tigran in 2004. The idea is to follow up with ...Rd8, putting immediate pressure on the d4-pawn. Today, this line is considered the most promising way for Black to equalize the game.}) 10. Nb5 $1 {This move may seem artificial at first glance, but it allows us to defend our d4 pawn while gaining a tempo against Black's queen on d6.} Qd7 {Naturally, Black doesn't want to play 10...Qd8, as their plan relies on the quick development of the rook to d8.} 11. Kb1 ({This is White's main line. This is a very serious continuation, but there are many variations to study, and the resulting positions are quite complex. I'll try to provide some key points, but then we'll move on to} 11. Bh6 {, which is my main recommendation.}) 11... Rd8 12. d5 a6 $1 (12... Ne5 $6 13. Qc2 $1 {± Anand-Mamedyarov, 2011.}) 13. Nc3 (13. dxc6 Qxd2 14. Rxd2 Rxd2 15. Bxd2 axb5 16. cxb7 Bxb7 17. Bxb5 f5 $1 {Where Black has enough counterplay for the missing pawn, for example:} 18. exf5 Bd5 $1 19. a3 Rb8 {∞ (( 19.b3 gxf5 ∞ where 20.Ne2? is not working because of 20...Bxb3 ∓ ))}) 13... Qe8 $1 (13... Na5 $6 14. Bd4 $1 {⩲}) 14. Qc1 (14. Qc1 {And now you need to study both} Na7 {, with the potential idea of ...Nb5 in the future, and the main line 14...Na5 .}) 14... Na5 (14... Na5 {Now White has several interesting moves:} 15. h4 {, 15.Bh6 , 15.Nge2 , and 15.g4 . It's certainly possible to explore this line further on your own if you like this position, but after many hours of analysis I've concluded that it's not easy for White to find an objective advantage. Black seemed to have sufficient resources. While these lines are intriguing, opting for 11. Kb1 would have required exploring various other theoretical chapters, which could have been too overwhelming for most readers.}) (14... Na7 $5 {With ...Nb5 next.}) *

