 Black plays the strongest moves, but White will still obtain pleasant and at least slightly better positions.} 16. h4 Qg4 {What follows is a line that is objectively not good for Black, but it is crucial for correctly evaluating the position.} 17. h5 g5 18. fxg5 Nxf3 19. gxf6 $1 {An important intermezzo. Now Black has to exchange the queens.} Qg5+ (19... Nd4 20. fxe7 {+- Black's knight on b6 is hanging. (19...exf6 20.gxf3 Qg5+ 21.Qxg5+ fxg5 11.Rd6! +- White has a winning advantage thanks to the pieces' activity. Also, it's very likely that Black will lose the g5-pawn. )}) 20. Qxg5+ Nxg5 21. fxe7 Re8 22. Rd6 $3 {A crucial move—without it, White would be in a lost position, and the entire variation would be unplayable for White.} Nd7 23. Nd5 $1 {[%csl Ge7][%cal Gd5c7] Another crucial move. Not only defending the pawn on e7, but also introducing the idea of forking the rooks with Nc7.} (23. Nd5 {A sample continuation might be} Nxe4 24. Re6 Ng5 25. Re3 b5 26. h6 Bb7 27. Rh5 Nf7 28. Nc7 {+- as in Hammer-Erdos 2012.}) *

