s the most ambitious continuation.} fxe5 17. Nxe5 Qd6 18. Nf3 c5 {White has regained the sacrificed pawn, but Black has developed and stabilized the knight on d4. While Black's position remains very risky from a human perspective, the computer is able to find sufficient resources to defend.} (18... c5 {My main recommendation is} 19. Bd3 {, a move played by Caruana in December 2023, but I would also like to explore the more concrete moves 19.Ng5 and 19.h4 .}) 19. Bd3 $5 {A very interesting move that was played in a rapid game between Caruana and MVL in December 2023.} (19. Ng5 {Now Black will need to play a few precise moves, but the final position will be entirely acceptable for them.} Qe7 $1 {(( 19...Qc7? 20.Na4!! Nxa4 21.Bc4+ +- ))} 20. Nd5 $5 {White's logical continuation. (( 20.Na4?? Nxa4 21.Bc4+ Be6 -+ Now Black's queen on e7 is defending the bishop on e6.))} Nxd5 21. Bc4 Kh8 22. Bxd5 Qg7 23. Qxg7+ Kxg7 24. Rdf1 {The endgame is equal.}) 19... Qe7 $2 {As played in the aforementioned Caruana-MVL game in 2013. However, it is an error that Caruana could have exploited by playing h4!.} 20. h4 Qg7 ({After} 20... Bg4 {we can continue with} 21. h5 Bxh5 22. Rxh5 $1 gxh5 23. Qxb6 {+-}) 21. Qg5 $1 {[%csl Rc5] White attacks the pawn on c5.} Ne6 22. Qe3 $18 {[%cal Gh4h5] White will continue with h4-h5, and Black's position is already lost.} *

