s the most ambitious continuation.} fxe5 17. Nxe5 Qd6 18. Nf3 c5 {White has regained the sacrificed pawn, but Black has developed and stabilized the knight on d4. While Black's position remains very risky from a human perspective, the computer is able to find sufficient resources to defend.} (18... c5 {My main recommendation is} 19. Bd3 {, a move played by Caruana in December 2023, but I would also like to explore the more concrete moves 19.Ng5 and 19.h4 .}) 19. Bd3 $5 {A very interesting move that was played in a rapid game between Caruana and MVL in December 2023.} (19. Ng5 {Now Black will need to play a few precise moves, but the final position will be entirely acceptable for them.} Qe7 $1 {(( 19...Qc7? 20.Na4!! Nxa4 21.Bc4+ +- ))} 20. Nd5 $5 {White's logical continuation. (( 20.Na4?? Nxa4 21.Bc4+ Be6 -+ Now Black's queen on e7 is defending the bishop on e6.))} Nxd5 21. Bc4 Kh8 22. Bxd5 Qg7 23. Qxg7+ Kxg7 24. Rdf1 {The endgame is equal.}) 19... Qf4+ {This is the move I would expect in a practical game. Black wants to exchange queens immediately to relieve the tension. However, White will have good chances in the resulting endgame.} 20. Qxf4 Rxf4 {We are following the game Sadler-Svidler, 2013.} 21. Rhf1 {[%cal Gf3d4] White threatens to capture on d4.} Nxf3 22. Rxf3 Rxf3 23. gxf3 Be6 24. Kd2 Rd8 25. Ke3 $14 {[%cal Gf3f4,Gh2h4] White has good chances in this endgame due to the strong central pawns. White can continue with f3-f4 and then h4-h5.} *

