1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} d5 {Black has several other minor options on move 3, with the most common being 3...Nc6. We analyze all of them in Chapter 1.} 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 {This is the starting position of our Grünfeld Variation.} e5 $5 {Black plays 8...e5 without ...Nc6 so as to meet 9. d5 with 9...c6, immediately challenging our center. This idea was first seen back in 1933 in the game between Reuben Fine and Arthur Dake. However, it only gained fame in 1998 following the game Kramnik-Shirov, where Black emerged victorious.The most famous games in this variation are undoubtedly Anand-Gelfand in 2012, played in the third game of the World Championship match, and the 2016 Candidates Tournament game between Anish Giri and Fabiano Caruana. As you can see, this is a line with a lot of history!} 9. d5 c6 10. h4 $1 {There was an old saying: 'Against a flank attack, a counterattack in the center is usually strong,' but here things are reversed! 'Against a central attack, a flank attack is strong.'} h5 $2 {This move, which drastically prevents White's h4-h5, was played in the aforementioned Kramnik-Shirov game. However, modern engines clearly show that it is a mistake for Black.} 11. g4 $1 {This direct move immediately puts Black in a difficult position, unable to find a satisfactory continuation.} cxd5 (11... hxg4 12. h5 cxd5 13. exd5 {is just a different move order that leads to the same position.}) 12. exd5 Na6 13. d6 $1 {[%cal Ga2g8] This unusual move has a very clear idea: to open the a2-g8 diagonal for our bishop. The idea can be seen in the following logical continuation.} hxg4 14. h5 $1 Bf5 {Black supports the g6 pawn and also prepares ...Nb4 ideas.} (14... Be6 {Black continues developing, but after} 15. Ne4 {+- White can proceed with either h5-h6 or hxg6, and Black’s position is already collapsing due to the exposed vulnerability of the king.}) 15. fxg4 $1 {[%csl Rf5] White deflects Black's bishop from the strong f5 square.} Bxg4 16. hxg6 fxg6 17. Bxb6 $1 {[%cal Gf1c4] Bc4+ is coming, and Black has nothing better than to give up an exchange on f1. White is better.} (17. Bxb6 {For instance, after} Qxb6 18. Bc4+ {+- White is immediately winning.}) (17. Bxb6 {Or} Rxf1+ 18. Kxf1 Qxb6 19. Qd5+ Kf8 {where the simple} 20. Ne4 $5 {± is good enough for an advantage, or 20.Rh4! ± Bf5 21.Ne4 Nb4 22.Qb3 +- White's idea is Ng5, and Black's position is already lost.}) *

