1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} d5 {Black has several other minor options on move 3, with the most common being 3...Nc6. We analyze all of them in Chapter 1.} 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 {This is the starting position of our Grünfeld Variation.} e5 $5 {Black plays 8...e5 without ...Nc6 so as to meet 9. d5 with 9...c6, immediately challenging our center. This idea was first seen back in 1933 in the game between Reuben Fine and Arthur Dake. However, it only gained fame in 1998 following the game Kramnik-Shirov, where Black emerged victorious.The most famous games in this variation are undoubtedly Anand-Gelfand in 2012, played in the third game of the World Championship match, and the 2016 Candidates Tournament game between Anish Giri and Fabiano Caruana. As you can see, this is a line with a lot of history!} 9. d5 c6 10. h4 $1 {There was an old saying: 'Against a flank attack, a counterattack in the center is usually strong,' but here things are reversed! 'Against a central attack, a flank attack is strong.'} cxd5 11. exd5 N8d7 {[%csl Gg8,Gh7][%cal Gd7f6,Yf6g8,Yf6h7] This is by far Black's main move. The idea is to transfer the knight to f6, where it will join the defense of Black's king.} (11... h5 12. g4 $1 {transposes to 10...h5 lines.}) 12. h5 Nf6 (12... gxh5 {A computer move, but white is better anyway after} 13. Bh6 {⩲ or 13.O-O-O ⩲ .}) 13. h6 {Instead of following the highly theoretical path and over 200 high level games that begins with 13. hxg6, and instead of memorizing numerous lines that your opponents are also likely to have had memorized, I suggest 13. h6!?. This move has never been played before and offers White excellent chances to fight for an advantage. The fantastic aspect for us is that it’s highly unlikely our opponent will be prepared for this, and without proper preparation, playing as Black will not be easy at all.} (13. hxg6 fxg6 14. O-O-O Bd7 15. Kb1 Rc8 16. d6 e4 $1 {Black sacrifices a pawn, but the dark-squared bishop will be strong.} 17. fxe4 Ng4 $1 18. Bg5 Qe8 19. Nf3 {Black's best move is} Rf7 $3 {There are more than 50 games in this position, and although White has several interesting options, most of these have been extensively analyzed and are well known to experienced Grünfeld players.}) 13... Bh8 14. Rd1 $1 {[%csl Gd5] We need to defend the pawn on d5, but at the same time we don't want to commit our king to c1 where it could be more exposed to counterplay with moves like ...Bf5 and ...Rc8.} ({After} 14. O-O-O $6 Bd7 {(( 14...Bf5!? ))} 15. Kb1 Rc8 {Black has some initiative.}) 14... e4 $2 {This is a typical attempt in these positions. Black sacrifices a pawn to activate the dark-squared bishop, but this move will prove ineffective in this specific position.} 15. fxe4 Re8 {[%csl Re4] Black attacks the pawn on e4.} 16. Nf3 $1 {But White can continue with development, and if Black recaptures the pawn with...} Nxe4 17. Nxe4 Rxe4 18. Bd3 $1 Re8 19. O-O $18 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gd2f2,Gf3g5] White will have a strategically and dynamically winning position. The pawn on f7 is highly vulnerable, and Black has no realistic chance of finding a satisfactory defense. Qf2 and Ng5 could be our next couple of moves.} *

