Black will not be easy at all.} (13. hxg6 fxg6 14. O-O-O Bd7 15. Kb1 Rc8 16. d6 e4 $1 {Black sacrifices a pawn, but the dark-squared bishop will be strong.} 17. fxe4 Ng4 $1 18. Bg5 Qe8 19. Nf3 {Black's best move is} Rf7 $3 {There are more than 50 games in this position, and although White has several interesting options, most of these have been extensively analyzed and are well known to experienced Grünfeld players.}) 13... Bh8 14. Rd1 $1 {[%csl Gd5] We need to defend the pawn on d5, but at the same time we don't want to commit our king to c1 where it could be more exposed to counterplay with moves like ...Bf5 and ...Rc8.} ({After} 14. O-O-O $6 Bd7 {(( 14...Bf5!? ))} 15. Kb1 Rc8 {Black has some initiative.}) 14... Bd7 {This natural developing move is not wrong in itself, but it requires very precise handling by Black.} 15. Nh3 {[%cal Gh3g5,Gh3f2,Gf2g4] White plans to continue with Nf2 or Ng5 and Nge4.} e4 $3 {The only move that prevents Black from entering an immediately inferior position. In my opinion, it's a very difficult move to find, because if Black wanted to play e5-e4, it would have been much more natural to do so on the previous move.} 16. Nxe4 ({This is safer than} 16. fxe4 {.}) 16... Nbxd5 (16... Nfxd5 17. Bd4 {⩲ As we can see, after the imminent exchange of the dark-squared bishops, the pawn on h6 will become a significant asset for White, as it will one day enable troublesome mating threats.}) 17. Nxf6+ Nxf6 18. Ng5 $14 {[%cal Ge1f2] The position is symmetrical, and it’s clear that White has a risk-free initiative here. The king will be very well-placed on f2, while all other pieces are more active. The pawn on h6 will be a valuable asset for the future.} *

