1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} d5 {Black has several other minor options on move 3, with the most common being 3...Nc6. We analyze all of them in Chapter 1.} 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 (5... Nf6 $2 {This move makes no sense bacause Black's bishop on g7 will no longer influence White's center for the next few moves.} 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Nge2 {±}) 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 Nc6 {[%csl Rd4] Black attacks the pawn on d4, forcing White to play d4-d5.} 8. d5 {[%csl Rc6] White can win some important tempi by attacking Black's knight.} Ne5 9. f4 $1 Ng4 {Black's only move.} 10. Bb5+ c6 $5 {This move was reintroduced into practice a few months ago by the strong Russian grandmaster Daniil Dubov.} (10... Kf8 $2 {Black loses castling rights, and White is better after any move. For example} 11. Bc5 {± Black’s knight on g4 and king on f8 are poorly positioned. White can proceed with standard developing moves, enjoying a much better position.}) 11. dxc6 O-O $1 {What follows is a typical computer-style line, which Dubov was undoubtedly familiar with. Black needs to know a great deal to hold the position, and even the young Russian GM made a mistake at some point.} (11... bxc6 $2 12. Bxc6+ Bd7 13. Bxb6 $1 axb6 14. Bxa8 Qxa8 15. Nge2 {+- Tang-Bernadskiy, 2014.}) (11... Qxd1+ $2 12. Nxd1 $1 O-O 13. Bc5 bxc6 14. Bxc6 Rb8 15. Bxe7 {±}) 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. c7 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Gc7d8] White keeps their pawn alive and gains a tempo against Black's rook.} Rf8 14. Bc5 {It seems that White is winning, but with a series of precise moves, the computer manages to hold.} (14. Bd2 $5 {deserves attention.}) 14... Bxc3+ $1 ({Black needs to exchange some pieces to simplify the position.} 14... Bd7 $2 15. Nge2 {+-}) 15. bxc3 Bd7 {Only move.} 16. Bxd7 Nxd7 17. Bxe7 Rfe8 {[%csl Re4][%cal Ge8e4] Black recovers the pawn by capturing on e4 on the next move.} 18. Bd8 Rxe4+ 19. Ne2 {Now it is crucial for Black to capture the pawn on c7 in time.} Nc5 ({Black's best move.} 19... Ne3 $2 {was played in Xu-Dubov 2024, but after} 20. Kf2 $1 {+- White is winning.}) 20. h3 Ne3 {Only now Black has to play ...Ne3. For sure Dubov mixed up the lines.} 21. Kf2 {[%csl Gc5,Rh3]} Rc8 {[%cal Ge3d5,Gd5c7] Black's idea is ...Nd5-...Nxc7.} 22. Nd4 {[%cal Gd4b5] We are threatening Nb5.} a6 $1 {[%csl Rb5]} ({Black prevents Nb5.} 22... Nd5 $2 23. Nb5 {+-}) 23. Nb3 $5 {This is White's best try.} Nxb3 24. Rae1 $1 (24. axb3 Nd5 {Black manages to equalize immediately.}) 24... Nc5 25. Rxe3 Rxe3 26. Kxe3 Ne6 27. Rd1 Nxc7 28. Rd7 Ne6 29. Bf6 $14 {Black managed to recapture the pawn by playing with maximum precision up to move 29. However, this position, while likely defensible by an engine, is extremely demanding for Black in a practical game. We can conclude that Dubov's 10...c6 is not losing, but it is far from guaranteeing equality for Black.} *

