1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} d5 {Black has several other minor options on move 3, with the most common being 3...Nc6. We analyze all of them in Chapter 1.} 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 (5... Nf6 $2 {This move makes no sense bacause Black's bishop on g7 will no longer influence White's center for the next few moves.} 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Nge2 {±}) 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 Be6 {Aronian liked to play this move back in 2014. Black's idea is to provoke d4-d5, then retreat the bishop and continue with c7-c6 or e7-e6, challenging White's pawn on d5. If White doesn't play d4-d5, Black will try to exploit the c4 square. However, as we will see, this approach is not engine-approved.} 9. h4 Bc4 10. b3 Bxf1 11. Kxf1 $16 {[%cal Gg1e2,Gd4d5,Gh4h5] White will continue with Nge2, d5 and h5.} *

