1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} d5 {Black has several other minor options on move 3, with the most common being 3...Nc6. We analyze all of them in Chapter 1.} 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 (5... Nf6 $2 {This move makes no sense bacause Black's bishop on g7 will no longer influence White's center for the next few moves.} 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Nge2 {±}) 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 Nc6 9. O-O-O a5 {[%cal Ga5a4,Gc6a5] Black aims to continue with a5-a4 and only then play ...Na5, as White will not be able to cover the c4 square by playing b2-b3.} 10. d5 $1 {We force Black's knight to move immediately, making the ...a4-...Na5 plan no longer available.} Ne5 11. Bxb6 {[%csl Rb5] We take advantage of the weakness on the b5 square.} cxb6 12. f4 Nd7 13. e5 Nc5 14. Nf3 Bf5 15. Qe3 $16 {[%cal Gf3d4] White will continue with Nd4 on the next move and stand better, thanks to the strong center.} *

