1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 Bg7 4. e4 O-O 5. Nc3 d6 6. Nge2 {In this second section, we will analyze the King's Indian Defense. For practical reasons, I will refer to it as KID from now on.} a6 $5 (6... e5 {This is a typical move for Black in the KID, but against the Saemisch, it doesn't work so well. We will analyze it in Chapter 8.}) (6... c6 7. Be3 a6 {This one is an old variation; Black's idea is b7-b5. We will analyze it in Chapter 9.}) (6... Nc6 7. Be3 a6 {This is named 'Panno Variation'. It's a serious line, and we will study it in Chapter 10.}) 7. Be3 Nbd7 8. Qd2 b5 {This line has gained a lot of popularity in the last five years. In fact, the strong GM Gawain Jones suggests this system against the Saemisch 6. Nge2 in his Chessable course Lifetime Repertoires: King's Indian Defense - Part 1. It's important that we study it thoroughly, and we will do so in Chapter 11.} *

