1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} Bg7 4. e4 O-O 5. Nc3 d6 (5... d6 {This is the starting position of the Saemisch Variation in the King's Indian Defense. The most common moves played by White here are} 6. Be3 {and 6.Bg5 . However, during my career, I have always preferred 6.Nge2 . The reason is that it keeps the bishop on c1 flexible. Depending on the situation, the bishop might move to e3, g5, or stay on c1 for a while, giving us time to focus on other important moves.}) 6. Nge2 e5 {This is the typical continuation for Black in the King's Indian Defense, and many classic games have been played from this position. However, nowadays, the move e7-e5 is rarely seen when White opts for the Saemisch system.Even though this variation has fallen out of favor, I believe it’s still important to dedicate a chapter to it, as it was once played by some of the strongest players in the world.} 7. d5 {This is the strongest move according to the engine. If you choose to trust the computer over me, then you can play it. Since we have closed the center, Black can now proceed with the thematic f7-f5 push.} Nh5 $5 8. Be3 f5 9. Qd2 $14 {Of course, White still has good chances in this position, but it is much more challenging to play. So, if you prefer to see an evaluation of +0.60 and enter a very difficult position where you will need to make many critical decisions, rather than opting for +0.35 and playing a safer and more intuitive position, that choice is entirely up to you.} *

