1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Nge2 {In this chapter, we will examine a plan that was very popular a few years ago. Black aims to execute the b7-b5 push, and to prepare for it, they play a6 and c6 first. These moves can be played in either order.} c6 (6... a6 7. Be3 c6 {and it leads to the same.}) 7. Be3 a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Black is now ready for b7-b5.} 8. g4 $5 {According to the engines, this ambitious move creates serious challenges for Black. It is also very logical because Black has spent some tempi playing a6-c6, so our fast Kingside attack is entirely justified.} b5 {This is Black's coherent continuation according to the variation that he has chosen.} 9. h4 $1 {We are taking advantage of the fact that Black has spent three tempi creating counterplay on the queenside a6-c6-b5, and we aim to punish this with a direct attack on the kingside.} h5 {This is Black's most principled move, as it stops White's h4-h5 push. In the King's Indian Defense, Black rarely knows the exact objective evaluation of a move, but it is usually best to play the most principled moves. Even if these moves are not objectively ideal, they will require a lot of precision from White to take advantage of them. In this case, we are playing from the White side. While the engine evaluation already indicates that White has a superior position, we need to understand exactly how to continue.} (9... Qa5 $6 {and here White should have continued with} 10. h5 $1 {± Where Black's position may be already objectively lost due to our strong initiative on the kingside.}) 10. Ng3 {This extremely strong theoretical novelty completely refutes Black's variation.} (10. e5 {This is White's most popular move, but after} dxe5 $1 11. dxe5 Nxg4 $5 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. fxg4 Bxg4 {∞ The arising endgame is complicated and should be objectively fine for Black.}) 10... hxg4 $1 {Black's most principled continuation.} 11. h5 $1 {The game gets concrete.} e5 $2 {Black loses due to a highly instructive refutation.} 12. h6 $1 Bh8 13. h7+ $1 Nxh7 14. Qd2 $18 {[%cal Gd2h2] Qh2 is coming, and Black is busted.} *

