1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Nge2 {In this chapter, we will examine a plan that was very popular a few years ago. Black aims to execute the b7-b5 push, and to prepare for it, they play a6 and c6 first. These moves can be played in either order.} c6 (6... a6 7. Be3 c6 {and it leads to the same.}) 7. Be3 a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Black is now ready for b7-b5.} 8. a4 {[%cal Rb7b5] Preventing the b7-b5 idea.} a5 {[%cal Gb8a6,Ga6b4] Black's usual continuation, with the idea that now their knight on b8 has an excellent square on b4.} 9. Qd2 Na6 10. g4 $16 {I need to admit that, according to modern engines, White is better also here, and this means that 8. a4 can be an excellent alternative for White.} *

