1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Nge2 Nc6 7. Be3 a6 {This is the starting position of the so-called Panno Variation. Black's idea is to push b7-b5. It is a positional line, and instead of memorizing a lot of variations, you should focus on understanding the ideas and plans.} 8. Qd2 {[%csl Gd2] This move is always useful for White in the Saemisch systems.} b5 $2 {This is premature for Black.} 9. cxb5 axb5 10. Nxb5 {Black doesn't have enough compensation.} Na5 {[%cal Ra5c4,Ra5b3] An important trick to remember; Black is threatening both Nc4 and Nb3.} 11. Nc1 $16 {We defend from both threats, and we can safely continue to play with an extra pawn.} *

