1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Nge2 Nc6 7. Be3 a6 {This is the starting position of the so-called Panno Variation. Black's idea is to push b7-b5. It is a positional line, and instead of memorizing a lot of variations, you should focus on understanding the ideas and plans.} 8. Qd2 {[%csl Gd2] This move is always useful for White in the Saemisch systems.} Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5] Historically, this has been Black's main move. The idea is quite clear: b7-b5.} 9. Rc1 $1 {This is an important prophylactic move. The idea is that now Black cannot play b7-b5 because of the hanging knight on c6.} (9. Rb1 {This would be our move in case of 7...Bd7, but here it’s not as effective because after} b5 10. cxb5 axb5 11. b4 {Black is in time to play} e5 $1 12. d5 Ne7 {∞ This position occurred in my game against Efimenko back in 2002. Although I managed to win that game, Black's position is objectively good. They can continue with Bd7, followed by Bc6.}) 9... e5 $6 {The e7-e5 plan is not good for Black in the Panno.} ({After} 9... b5 $2 10. cxb5 axb5 11. Nxb5 $1 Rxb5 12. Rxc6 {± Black doesn't have compensation for the missing pawn.}) 10. d5 Na5 {This move was played in the game Basso-Mazi 2016. Now White's best continuation is Nd1!} (10... Ne7 11. Nd1 {White's play will be very similar to the 9...Bd7 10. Nd1 e5 variation.}) 11. Nd1 $1 {[%cal Rd2a5] Our queen is threatening the black's knight on a5.} c5 (11... c5 {Now, White has many good moves, like} 12. Ng3 {or 12.b3 . But if you want to play more concretely, you can try b4.}) 12. b4 $5 cxb4 13. Qxb4 {[%cal Ge3b6] White is threatening Bb6.} b6 14. Nec3 $16 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gc3a4,Ga4b6] Na4 is coming next, and most likely Black will lose a pawn as after 15.Na4 Nd7 White can continue with 16.Nxb6 Nxb6 17.Qxa5 .} *

