1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Nge2 Nc6 7. Be3 a6 {This is the starting position of the so-called Panno Variation. Black's idea is to push b7-b5. It is a positional line, and instead of memorizing a lot of variations, you should focus on understanding the ideas and plans.} 8. Qd2 {[%csl Gd2] This move is always useful for White in the Saemisch systems.} Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5] Historically, this has been Black's main move. The idea is quite clear: b7-b5.} 9. Rc1 $1 {This is an important prophylactic move. The idea is that now Black cannot play b7-b5 because of the hanging knight on c6.} (9. Rb1 {This would be our move in case of 7...Bd7, but here it’s not as effective because after} b5 10. cxb5 axb5 11. b4 {Black is in time to play} e5 $1 12. d5 Ne7 {∞ This position occurred in my game against Efimenko back in 2002. Although I managed to win that game, Black's position is objectively good. They can continue with Bd7, followed by Bc6.}) 9... Bd7 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Gb7b5] This is Black's logical continuation. Now the knight on c6 is protected, and Black is ready for b7-b5; that's why our next move is very important.} 10. Nd1 $1 (10. Nd1 {This is a very strong positional move. Generally, our knight is ideally placed on the f2 square, but in this case, the main idea is that after} b5 {, we can continue with} 11. c5 {. If Black responds with dxc5, we can recapture with the rook. This is a crucial detail because if we had to recapture with the pawn, our position would not be so good. By recapturing with the rook, we maintain a strong center and can use our rook on the c file to apply pressure.}) 10... e5 {As I have already mentioned, the move e7-e5 is generally not good in the Panno variation, and here it is not an exception.} 11. d5 Ne7 12. Nf2 {[%cal Gg2g3,Gf1g2] Our idea will be to continue with g3-Bg2-O-O.} Ne8 {Black is following their typical King's Indian plan: pushing f7-f5.} 13. g3 c5 14. b4 {White can continue their queenside play, with a better position.} b6 15. Bg2 f5 16. O-O Kh8 17. Rb1 $16 {[%cal Gb1b3,Gf1b1] We can continue with Rb3-Rfb1, and we will take bxc5 at the most convenient moment.} *

