1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Nge2 Nc6 7. Be3 a6 {This is the starting position of the so-called Panno Variation. Black's idea is to push b7-b5. It is a positional line, and instead of memorizing a lot of variations, you should focus on understanding the ideas and plans.} 8. Qd2 {[%csl Gd2] This move is always useful for White in the Saemisch systems.} Bd7 {This is a very serious variation. Black isn't playing Rb8 yet because the rook might also prove useful on the a file.} 9. Rb1 $1 {This is the continuation I like the most against the 8...Bd7 variation. Our idea is to prepare b2-b4, which would allow us to take space on the queenside.} (9. Rc1 {This was our move in the 8...Rb8 variation, but here Black is fine after} b5 $1 10. cxb5 axb5 11. Nxb5 Rxa2 $1 {And Black's rook has indeed proven to be useful on the a file. Now the attempts to trap Black's rook don’t work:} 12. Na3 $6 Qb8 $1 {Black is threatening our pawn on b2, and} 13. Rb1 {is not working because of} Rxa3 $1 {-+ .}) 9... b5 $2 {Compared to the 9. Rc1 line, this move doesn't work now, and this is a key tactical detail that highlights why 9. Rb1 is more precise than 9. Rc1.} 10. cxb5 axb5 11. Nxb5 Rxa2 12. Na3 $1 {The difference is that now our b2 pawn is well defended, and against ...Qb8 we can continue with Nc3.} Qb8 13. Nc3 $18 {[%cal Gc3a2,Gc3b1]} (13. Nc3 {White is winning because after} Rxa3 14. bxa3 {, our rook on b1 is defended.}) *

