1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Nge2 Nc6 7. Be3 a6 {This is the starting position of the so-called Panno Variation. Black's idea is to push b7-b5. It is a positional line, and instead of memorizing a lot of variations, you should focus on understanding the ideas and plans.} 8. Qd2 {[%csl Gd2] This move is always useful for White in the Saemisch systems.} Bd7 {This is a very serious variation. Black isn't playing Rb8 yet because the rook might also prove useful on the a file.} 9. Rb1 $1 {This is the continuation I like the most against the 8...Bd7 variation. Our idea is to prepare b2-b4, which would allow us to take space on the queenside.} (9. Rc1 {This was our move in the 8...Rb8 variation, but here Black is fine after} b5 $1 10. cxb5 axb5 11. Nxb5 Rxa2 $1 {And Black's rook has indeed proven to be useful on the a file. Now the attempts to trap Black's rook don’t work:} 12. Na3 $6 Qb8 $1 {Black is threatening our pawn on b2, and} 13. Rb1 {is not working because of} Rxa3 $1 {-+ .}) 9... Rb8 {Black realizes that the rook may no longer be useful on the 'a' file, so they play Rb8 to prepare b7-b5.} 10. b4 b5 11. cxb5 $1 {After the pawns exchange on b5, Black's b5 pawn will be a weakness.} axb5 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Ge7e5] If you remember, in the 8...Rb8 9. Rb1 variation, we saw that Black can reach the same position, but with their pawn on e5 instead of the bishop on d7. However, here White is better after d5.} 12. d5 $1 Ne5 13. Nd4 e6 $1 {Black is challenging our pawn on d5, and it’s important for us to ignore it and continue with 14. Be2.} (13... Nc4 $2 14. Bxc4 bxc4 15. b5 {+- We have a very strong a pawn, and our knight on d4 is dominating the position.}) 14. Be2 $1 (14. Ndxb5 $2 exd5 15. exd5 Bxb5 16. Bxb5 {(( 16.Nxb5 Nxd5!! 17.Qxd5 c6 18.Qxd6 Qh4+ 19.g3 Qh5 -+ ))} Rxb5 17. Nxb5 Nc4 {-+ When Nxe3 followed by Re8 is coming.}) 14... exd5 15. exd5 Re8 16. O-O $16 {[%csl Rb5,Gc6] White's pieces are better placed, and Black also has the additional problems of the weak b5 pawn and the c6 square. White is better, and you can check the game Morozevich-Illescas 2011 if you want to see a great example of how to handle this position.} *

