1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Nge2 Nc6 7. Be3 a6 {This is the starting position of the so-called Panno Variation. Black's idea is to push b7-b5. It is a positional line, and instead of memorizing a lot of variations, you should focus on understanding the ideas and plans.} 8. Qd2 {[%csl Gd2] This move is always useful for White in the Saemisch systems.} Na5 (8... Na5 {In my opinion, this is Black’s best continuation in the Panno variation. The reason is that it’s concrete, and it might disrupt our standard plans. Black immediately threatens the c4 pawn, and if we defend it with a move like} 9. Ng3 {, then after} b5 $1 10. cxb5 axb5 {, we cannot play} 11. Nxb5 {due to the} Nb3 $1 {idea. This is actually a key concept in the 8...Na5 Panno variation. For this reason, 9. Nc1 has traditionally been White’s main move in this position, as the knight on c1 controls the b3 square. However, I want to offer you a relatively fresh direction that is more ambitious for White, in my opinion.}) 9. Nf4 $5 {I like this fresh move for several reasons. First, the knight is more active on f4 compared to being on c1. For instance, if Black plays e7-e5, our knight can immediately jump to d5. Second, it better supports a kingside attack than 9. Ng3, as our g pawn can now be pushed, and the knight on f4 can target the g6 pawn in some variations. The only drawback is that we lose the option of playing Bh6, as the knight is in the way.} e5 $2 {Black wants to punish our 9. Nf4 move.} 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 {We can now place our knight on the excellent d5 square.} 12. Nfd5 $16 {And this is a very important positional detail: our knight on f4 cannot be easily attacked, because if Black plays e7-e5, the knight can jump to d5.} *

