1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Nge2 Nc6 7. Be3 a6 {This is the starting position of the so-called Panno Variation. Black's idea is to push b7-b5. It is a positional line, and instead of memorizing a lot of variations, you should focus on understanding the ideas and plans.} 8. Qd2 {[%csl Gd2] This move is always useful for White in the Saemisch systems.} Na5 (8... Na5 {In my opinion, this is Black’s best continuation in the Panno variation. The reason is that it’s concrete, and it might disrupt our standard plans. Black immediately threatens the c4 pawn, and if we defend it with a move like} 9. Ng3 {, then after} b5 $1 10. cxb5 axb5 {, we cannot play} 11. Nxb5 {due to the} Nb3 $1 {idea. This is actually a key concept in the 8...Na5 Panno variation. For this reason, 9. Nc1 has traditionally been White’s main move in this position, as the knight on c1 controls the b3 square. However, I want to offer you a relatively fresh direction that is more ambitious for White, in my opinion.}) 9. Nf4 $5 {I like this fresh move for several reasons. First, the knight is more active on f4 compared to being on c1. For instance, if Black plays e7-e5, our knight can immediately jump to d5. Second, it better supports a kingside attack than 9. Ng3, as our g pawn can now be pushed, and the knight on f4 can target the g6 pawn in some variations. The only drawback is that we lose the option of playing Bh6, as the knight is in the way.} b5 {[%csl Rb3,Gf4] This is Black's standard continuation. They were playing it in the 9. Nc1 variation, and they should be even happier to play it now, where our knight from f4 is not controlling the b3 square.} 10. cxb5 $6 {Once again, White should not accept the pawn sacrifice. I've already explained the reasons behind this, but it's worth repeating to prevent you from making the same mistake in a game.} axb5 11. Bxb5 $2 Nb3 $17 {This is a typical tactical idea for Black in the 8...Na5 Panno.} *

