1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Nge2 Nc6 7. Be3 a6 {This is the starting position of the so-called Panno Variation. Black's idea is to push b7-b5. It is a positional line, and instead of memorizing a lot of variations, you should focus on understanding the ideas and plans.} 8. Qd2 {[%csl Gd2] This move is always useful for White in the Saemisch systems.} Na5 (8... Na5 {In my opinion, this is Black’s best continuation in the Panno variation. The reason is that it’s concrete, and it might disrupt our standard plans. Black immediately threatens the c4 pawn, and if we defend it with a move like} 9. Ng3 {, then after} b5 $1 10. cxb5 axb5 {, we cannot play} 11. Nxb5 {due to the} Nb3 $1 {idea. This is actually a key concept in the 8...Na5 Panno variation. For this reason, 9. Nc1 has traditionally been White’s main move in this position, as the knight on c1 controls the b3 square. However, I want to offer you a relatively fresh direction that is more ambitious for White, in my opinion.}) 9. Nf4 $5 {I like this fresh move for several reasons. First, the knight is more active on f4 compared to being on c1. For instance, if Black plays e7-e5, our knight can immediately jump to d5. Second, it better supports a kingside attack than 9. Ng3, as our g pawn can now be pushed, and the knight on f4 can target the g6 pawn in some variations. The only drawback is that we lose the option of playing Bh6, as the knight is in the way.} b5 {[%csl Rb3,Gf4] This is Black's standard continuation. They were playing it in the 9. Nc1 variation, and they should be even happier to play it now, where our knight from f4 is not controlling the b3 square.} 10. h4 $1 {We are ready to sacrifice our pawn on c4 to launch a fast attack on the kingside.} h5 {This move, which prevents h4-h5, is the most common and natural choice for Black. However, the problem is that White can continue with g2-g4. This illustrates why the knight on f4 is better placed than on g3.} 11. O-O-O (11. g4 {immediately, but after} Bxg4 $1 12. fxg4 Nxg4 {White still has the initiative, but things are less clear compared to the 11. [O-O-O] line.}) 11... Nxc4 {This is Black's most logical continuation.} 12. Bxc4 bxc4 13. g4 Bxg4 (13... hxg4 $2 {Taking on g4 with the pawn leads to an immediate disaster:} 14. h5 gxf3 15. h6 Bh8 16. h7+ Kg7 17. Qh2 Ng4 {Black's only move to prevent Qh6+.} 18. Nh5+ $1 gxh5 19. Qxh5 {+-}) (13... Nxg4 14. fxg4 Bxg4 15. Rdg1 Qd7 16. Rxg4 {We will see this same position in the 13...Bxg4 line.}) 14. fxg4 Nxg4 15. Rdg1 e5 $2 {This is a bad move.} 16. dxe5 dxe5 17. Nfd5 $1 {White has excellent attacking chances, and Black’s attempt to enter an endgame is not beneficial.} c6 18. Nb6 Qxd2+ 19. Bxd2 $16 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gb6c4] White will soon capture the pawn on c4, and Black's two pawns do not provide adequate compensation for the missing piece.} *

