 the problem is that White can continue with g2-g4. This illustrates why the knight on f4 is better placed than on g3.} 11. O-O-O (11. g4 {immediately, but after} Bxg4 $1 12. fxg4 Nxg4 {White still has the initiative, but things are less clear compared to the 11. [O-O-O] line.}) 11... Nxc4 {This is Black's most logical continuation.} 12. Bxc4 bxc4 13. g4 Bxg4 (13... hxg4 $2 {Taking on g4 with the pawn leads to an immediate disaster:} 14. h5 gxf3 15. h6 Bh8 16. h7+ Kg7 17. Qh2 Ng4 {Black's only move to prevent Qh6+.} 18. Nh5+ $1 gxh5 19. Qxh5 {+-}) (13... Nxg4 14. fxg4 Bxg4 15. Rdg1 Qd7 16. Rxg4 {We will see this same position in the 13...Bxg4 line.}) 14. fxg4 Nxg4 15. Rdg1 Qd7 $1 (15... Qd7 {Black's strongest defense. The idea is to meet} 16. Rxg4 {with} Qxg4 {, so that Black avoids ruining their kingside structure, which would happen if they recaptured with the h5 pawn.}) 16. Rxg4 $1 {Anyway, we need to eliminate Black's strong defender on g4.} Qxg4 17. Qf2 $1 {[%cal Rg4f3] This is an important move. We want to continue with Rg1, but it's first important to prevent Black's queen from entering into the f3 square.} e5 $1 {Finally, we managed to find a situation where the move e7-e5 is the strongest one for Black!} (17... Kh7 $2 {This could be an intuitive move, but it's bad.} 18. Rg1 Qd7 19. Nxh5 $1 gxh5 20. Qf3 f6 21. Qxh5+ Kg8 22. Rxg7+ Kxg7 23. Bh6+ {+- .}) 18. dxe5 dxe5 19. Nfd5 $16 {[%cal Gh1g1,Gd5f6] Black's position is very risky and objectively worse. We are ready to continue with ideas like 20. Rg1 or 20. Nf6+, and in a practical game, most players would likely collapse under the pressure in the next few moves.} *

