1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Nge2 Nc6 7. Be3 a6 {This is the starting position of the so-called Panno Variation. Black's idea is to push b7-b5. It is a positional line, and instead of memorizing a lot of variations, you should focus on understanding the ideas and plans.} 8. Qd2 {[%csl Gd2] This move is always useful for White in the Saemisch systems.} Na5 (8... Na5 {In my opinion, this is Black’s best continuation in the Panno variation. The reason is that it’s concrete, and it might disrupt our standard plans. Black immediately threatens the c4 pawn, and if we defend it with a move like} 9. Ng3 {, then after} b5 $1 10. cxb5 axb5 {, we cannot play} 11. Nxb5 {due to the} Nb3 $1 {idea. This is actually a key concept in the 8...Na5 Panno variation. For this reason, 9. Nc1 has traditionally been White’s main move in this position, as the knight on c1 controls the b3 square. However, I want to offer you a relatively fresh direction that is more ambitious for White, in my opinion.}) 9. Nf4 $5 {I like this fresh move for several reasons. First, the knight is more active on f4 compared to being on c1. For instance, if Black plays e7-e5, our knight can immediately jump to d5. Second, it better supports a kingside attack than 9. Ng3, as our g pawn can now be pushed, and the knight on f4 can target the g6 pawn in some variations. The only drawback is that we lose the option of playing Bh6, as the knight is in the way.} b5 {[%csl Rb3,Gf4] This is Black's standard continuation. They were playing it in the 9. Nc1 variation, and they should be even happier to play it now, where our knight from f4 is not controlling the b3 square.} 10. h4 $1 {We are ready to sacrifice our pawn on c4 to launch a fast attack on the kingside.} Nd7 $1 {This is Black's strongest defense according to the engine. The idea is to play ...e5, and after dxe5, recapture with the knight. This placement allows the knight to be excellently positioned, working well with the knight on a5 to pressure our c4 pawn.} 11. h5 {Black gave us the chance to advance h4-h5, and we should take it.} e5 12. Nfd5 $1 ({Of course, we don't want to capture} 12. dxe5 $6 {to allow Black to activate their knight after} Nxe5 $1 {∞ .}) 12... c6 $1 {Black is challenging our knight on d5, which has limited retreating squares. We must take 10...Nd7 seriously, as it’s the engine’s top move. Consequently, we need to study a few complicated lines to address this properly.} 13. hxg6 {We are sacrificing our knight on d5, but Black shouldn't take it immediately.} cxd5 $6 {We need to be prepared against this move, of course, but objectively we will be better in this variation.} 14. Bg5 $1 (14. gxh7+ $2 {Be careful to not confuse the move order.} Kh8 15. Bg5 {Because now} f6 {∓ is strong.}) 14... Nf6 {The next moves are forced.} (14... f6 $2 15. Bh6 {+-}) 15. gxh7+ Kh8 16. dxe5 dxe5 17. Nxd5 {[%csl Ra5,Rf6] We are now threatening to take everything on f6 because at the end of the line, Black's knight on a5 would be hanging.} Nxc4 (17... Be6 $2 18. Nxf6 Bxf6 19. Bxf6+ Qxf6 20. Qxa5 {+-}) 18. Bxc4 bxc4 19. Rd1 $1 {[%cal Gd5f6] We are now threatening Nxf6.} Bd7 $1 {This is Black's only defense.} 20. Nxf6 Bxf6 21. Bxf6+ Qxf6 22. Qxd7 $16 {We have two extra pawns. The only potential drawback is that Black's king might be safer than ours due to the h7 pawn serving as a good shield. However, this factor alone doesn’t provide sufficient compensation for the two missing pawns.} *

