and after dxe5, recapture with the knight. This placement allows the knight to be excellently positioned, working well with the knight on a5 to pressure our c4 pawn.} 11. h5 {Black gave us the chance to advance h4-h5, and we should take it.} e5 12. Nfd5 $1 ({Of course, we don't want to capture} 12. dxe5 $6 {to allow Black to activate their knight after} Nxe5 $1 {∞ .}) 12... c6 $1 {Black is challenging our knight on d5, which has limited retreating squares. We must take 10...Nd7 seriously, as it’s the engine’s top move. Consequently, we need to study a few complicated lines to address this properly.} 13. hxg6 {We are sacrificing our knight on d5, but Black shouldn't take it immediately.} fxg6 $1 ({Black's best defense.} 13... hxg6 $4 {This recapture loses immediately.} 14. Bh6 Bh8 15. g4 $1 {Preparing Qh2.} cxd5 16. Qh2 {+-}) 14. dxe5 Nxe5 {This recapture is tempting, but it's objectively bad.} 15. Bg5 $1 {Now I will provide the refutation line. You can study it if you wish, but it's not essential.} Naxc4 16. Bxc4 Nxc4 17. Qc1 $1 Qe8 {And now White has a cool tactical idea.} 18. Ne7+ Kh8 19. Rxh7+ $3 Kxh7 20. Ke2 {[%cal Gc1h1] Qh1+ is coming next.} Bf6 21. Qh1+ {The logical continuation.} Kg7 22. Qh6+ Kf7 23. Bxf6 Kxf6 24. Ncd5+ $1 {An important tactical idea of the position. We will sacrifice a knight, but we'll be able to capture the Black's queen.} cxd5 25. Nxd5+ Ke6 ({If} 25... Kf7 {, then after} 26. Qh7+ {, Black's king must move to e6, allowing 27. Nc7+.}) 26. Nc7+ Kd7 27. Nxe8 Rxe8 28. Rd1 $16 {Black has a rook, a knight, and a bishop for our queen and pawn. Normally, this would be a balanced material exchange, but in this position, the weaknesses in Black's king safety and the g6 pawn make the position significantly better for White.} *

