1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Nge2 a6 7. Be3 b5 {Usually, Black plays the moves ...b5 and ...Nbd7 starting with either one, but be careful! We reply differently to them.} 8. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5] In this case, White is ready to push h4-h5. Since Black revealed their cards by playing immediately ...b5, also we can do the same just on the other side of the board.} (8. Qd2 {is a possible move, but the problem is that after} c6 {White is transposing into the line with ...a6-c6 where instead of g4, White played Qd2. This version is an improved one for the Black side, though one can still argue that White has the advantage here. I suggest we go for a different approach.}) 8... Nbd7 $6 {The automatic response runs into h5.} 9. h5 {The opening of the h-file leads to a great advantage for the attacking side.} Nxh5 10. g4 Nhf6 11. Ng3 $16 {[%cal Gh1h7] Ideas of g5 and Qd2-h2 are available. There is no need to investigate this further, it is obvious that White has great attacking chances here.} *

