[Result "*"]
[ECO "E81"]
[PlyCount "35"]
[GameId "2160984183849064"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Nge2 a6 7. Be3 b5 {Usually, Black plays the moves ...b5 and ...Nbd7 starting with either one, but be careful! We reply differently to them.} 8. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5] In this case, White is ready to push h4-h5. Since Black revealed their cards by playing immediately ...b5, also we can do the same just on the other side of the board.} (8. Qd2 {is a possible move, but the problem is that after} c6 {White is transposing into the line with ...a6-c6 where instead of g4, White played Qd2. This version is an improved one for the Black side, though one can still argue that White has the advantage here. I suggest we go for a different approach.}) 8... h5 {Black should stop a white pawn coming to h5.} 9. Nf4 {We have seen this move in a similar position, the knight on f4 is a strong piece, and it is hard to kick it with ...e5, because that just further weakens the d5 square.} b4 {This is the best choice, but I should say it is already a tough move to play. Usually Black likes to keep the tension, not release it, since now White has a very strong pawn center.} 10. Ncd5 a5 {This move is quite slow, although it carries a positional trick we should be aware about.} 11. Nxf6+ {If you remember that trading the knight on f6 is good for White, 10...a5 shouldn't pose you a great threat during your game.} (11. Qd2 {This natural move can be met with} Nh7 $1 {and our knight on d5 is feeling the pressure all of a sudden. The positions get very messy after} 12. g4 {, but I believe White shouldn't give Black this opportunity.}) 11... Bxf6 12. Qd2 {Now Black's best is to transpose to a similar position we have seen also in the 10...Nc6 line.} e5 {This fails tactically.} 13. Nd5 $1 {Even stronger than dxe5.} Bxh4+ {The most critical line.} 14. Rxh4 $1 {Don't be afraid to give away the exchange, especially when it is the winning move!} Qxh4+ 15. g3 $3 {This is the final touch, White keeps the bishop on e3 for the moment to have Bg5 in case of ...Qd8.} Qxg3+ 16. Bf2 {[%csl Re7,Rf6] Now the queen left the diagonal so it doesn't control the f6 and e7 squares anymore.} Qxf3 17. Qh6 {[%cal Gd5e7] Ne7 is a mate in one threat.} Re8 18. Bg2 $18 {[%csl Rf6] Deflects the queen from the f6 square and White wins.} *

