1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Nge2 a6 7. Be3 b5 {Usually, Black plays the moves ...b5 and ...Nbd7 starting with either one, but be careful! We reply differently to them.} 8. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5] In this case, White is ready to push h4-h5. Since Black revealed their cards by playing immediately ...b5, also we can do the same just on the other side of the board.} (8. Qd2 {is a possible move, but the problem is that after} c6 {White is transposing into the line with ...a6-c6 where instead of g4, White played Qd2. This version is an improved one for the Black side, though one can still argue that White has the advantage here. I suggest we go for a different approach.}) 8... h5 {Black should stop a white pawn coming to h5.} 9. Nf4 {We have seen this move in a similar position, the knight on f4 is a strong piece, and it is hard to kick it with ...e5, because that just further weakens the d5 square.} b4 {This is the best choice, but I should say it is already a tough move to play. Usually Black likes to keep the tension, not release it, since now White has a very strong pawn center.} 10. Ncd5 a5 {This move is quite slow, although it carries a positional trick we should be aware about.} 11. Nxf6+ {If you remember that trading the knight on f6 is good for White, 10...a5 shouldn't pose you a great threat during your game.} (11. Qd2 {This natural move can be met with} Nh7 $1 {and our knight on d5 is feeling the pressure all of a sudden. The positions get very messy after} 12. g4 {, but I believe White shouldn't give Black this opportunity.}) 11... Bxf6 12. Qd2 {Now Black's best is to transpose to a similar position we have seen also in the 10...Nc6 line.} Nc6 13. O-O-O {[%cal Gf1e2,Gg2g4] If Black doesn't play ...e5, White can just continue to build up pressure on the kingside with Be2-g4.} e5 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. c5 $14 {[%cal Gb4b3,Ga2a3] This is the same as what we have seen after the 10...Nc6 move order, Black should maintain the pawn on d6 as it is, while after Kb1 to tuck our king away from the c-file, cxd6 will become a serious question.} *

