1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Nge2 a6 7. Be3 b5 {Usually, Black plays the moves ...b5 and ...Nbd7 starting with either one, but be careful! We reply differently to them.} 8. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5] In this case, White is ready to push h4-h5. Since Black revealed their cards by playing immediately ...b5, also we can do the same just on the other side of the board.} (8. Qd2 {is a possible move, but the problem is that after} c6 {White is transposing into the line with ...a6-c6 where instead of g4, White played Qd2. This version is an improved one for the Black side, though one can still argue that White has the advantage here. I suggest we go for a different approach.}) 8... h5 {Black should stop a white pawn coming to h5.} 9. Nf4 {We have seen this move in a similar position, the knight on f4 is a strong piece, and it is hard to kick it with ...e5, because that just further weakens the d5 square.} b4 {This is the best choice, but I should say it is already a tough move to play. Usually Black likes to keep the tension, not release it, since now White has a very strong pawn center.} 10. Ncd5 Nc6 {Not a preffered square for the knight, but honestly Black couldn't waste another tempo on a pawn move to protect b4.} 11. Nxf6+ {It is in White's interest to trade the pair of knights, so that g4 will be easier to achieve.} Bxf6 12. Qd2 e5 {The only move that justifies the placement of Black's pieces. Also seemingly it wins the pawn on h4!} 13. dxe5 Bxh4+ {Of course, this is met with Rxh4! and Black's position is dubious.} 14. Rxh4 $1 Qxh4+ 15. Bf2 Qg5 16. exd6 cxd6 17. O-O-O $16 {The king on c1 is very safe, and there is nothing good to be said about Black's position except the extra material. For this reason, White is better.} *

