1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Nge2 a6 7. Be3 Nbd7 {The system with 6...a6 and 7...Nbd7 is an interesting way to approach the Saemisch, that was also recommended by Jones Gawain in his Chessable Course about the King's Indian. There are some lines that are very wild, but I will try to tame them a bit, in order to preserve our positional trumps for a long-term advantage.} 8. Qd2 ({Now} 8. h4 {would make little sense, because the last developing move of Black can't be punished concretely.}) 8... c5 {This old line also exists, but in my opinion, it is a bad one, because White has the strategical response dxc5.} 9. dxc5 $5 {And I'm trying to argue that the knight will be misplaced either on d7 after ...dxc5, either on c5 in case of ...Nxc5. In both cases, the knight would be happier to be on c6.} Nxc5 10. Rd1 $14 {[%csl Ge2][%cal Ge2f4,Ge2d4,Ge2c1,Gf1e2,Ge1g1] This Maroczy position is good for White, because Black's knight is misplaced on c5. It would rather like to be on a safe square like c6. In the current position, it can easily get pushed back with b4, if ...Ne6 happens, in the future Nd5 will be strong because if Black recaptures, the knight will be completely doomed.} (10. Rd1 {In essence, White should try to just develop safely and not trade the c5 knight for the knight on e2, that's why after} Ne6 11. Nc1 {should be preferred.}) *

