[GameId "2160984183959662"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Nge2 a6 7. Be3 Nbd7 {The system with 6...a6 and 7...Nbd7 is an interesting way to approach the Saemisch, that was also recommended by Jones Gawain in his Chessable Course about the King's Indian. There are some lines that are very wild, but I will try to tame them a bit, in order to preserve our positional trumps for a long-term advantage.} 8. Qd2 ({Now} 8. h4 {would make little sense, because the last developing move of Black can't be punished concretely.}) 8... c5 {This old line also exists, but in my opinion, it is a bad one, because White has the strategical response dxc5.} 9. dxc5 $5 {And I'm trying to argue that the knight will be misplaced either on d7 after ...dxc5, either on c5 in case of ...Nxc5. In both cases, the knight would be happier to be on c6.} dxc5 10. Rd1 {And again Black's knight on d7 is a sad piece. Let's check how the game can continue.} Qc7 11. Nf4 e6 12. Nd3 $1 {A strong move, ...Ne5 was a positional threat, so I stopped it in time.} b6 13. Bf4 e5 {This move was played in my game against Smirin, but this is just a desperate move. Black will never be in time to reach the d4 square.} (13... Qc6 {was a better try, but still Black's position is bad, the pieces are not coordinated so we can look on the kingside as well.} 14. Bh6 Bb7 15. h4 {± With h5 next and Black has no counterplay whatsoever.}) 14. Bg5 Re8 15. Be2 Nf8 16. Nd5 {White occupies it first, and Black should take it.} Nxd5 17. cxd5 {[%cal Gd1c1,Gb2b4]} (17. cxd5 {Not a lot can be said about Black's pieces. The position is very unpleasant. Now what was left for me to do is to open the queenside and maximize my piece activity. For instance,} Nd7 18. Rc1 {± as in Dreev-Smirin, Dos Hermanas 2001.}) *

