1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Nge2 a6 7. Be3 Nbd7 {The system with 6...a6 and 7...Nbd7 is an interesting way to approach the Saemisch, that was also recommended by Jones Gawain in his Chessable Course about the King's Indian. There are some lines that are very wild, but I will try to tame them a bit, in order to preserve our positional trumps for a long-term advantage.} 8. Qd2 ({Now} 8. h4 {would make little sense, because the last developing move of Black can't be punished concretely.}) 8... b5 9. h4 {Now, this move is a good idea, Black committed to playing ...b5, so we as well can start our counterplay on the kingside.} (9. cxb5 {I don't recommend you to take this pawn, Black is fast at organizing counterplay against White's center.} axb5 10. Nxb5 c6 11. Nbc3 e5 {...d5 is coming next, with a very unclear battle ahead.} 12. Ng3 d5 {∞ .}) 9... h5 {Black can't really continue without this move.} (9... Nb6 {is met with} 10. Nf4 Nxc4 11. Bxc4 bxc4 12. h5 {± And funnily enough this is the same position as in the Panno variation! Only that there, the knight arrived to c4 from a5, in this chapter, from b6.}) 10. O-O-O Bb7 {This is a good way to keep the tension for the moment, also it fights against g4, as it puts more pressure on the e4 pawn.} 11. Kb1 {A good reply; now cxb5 is threatened, as we defended a2.} (11. g4 $5 {is a very messy continuation, for the brave hearted this can be an interesting alternative to look into.}) 11... bxc4 $6 {This is conceptually not advisable, as it releases the tension, but White can even punish it directly.} 12. g4 $1 {This works now, as ...b5-b4 is not an option anymore.} hxg4 13. Ng3 $16 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gh4h5] Keeps e4 protected and White can continue their attack with h5.} *

