1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Nge2 a6 7. Be3 Nbd7 {The system with 6...a6 and 7...Nbd7 is an interesting way to approach the Saemisch, that was also recommended by Jones Gawain in his Chessable Course about the King's Indian. There are some lines that are very wild, but I will try to tame them a bit, in order to preserve our positional trumps for a long-term advantage.} 8. Qd2 ({Now} 8. h4 {would make little sense, because the last developing move of Black can't be punished concretely.}) 8... b5 9. h4 {Now, this move is a good idea, Black committed to playing ...b5, so we as well can start our counterplay on the kingside.} (9. cxb5 {I don't recommend you to take this pawn, Black is fast at organizing counterplay against White's center.} axb5 10. Nxb5 c6 11. Nbc3 e5 {...d5 is coming next, with a very unclear battle ahead.} 12. Ng3 d5 {∞ .}) 9... h5 {Black can't really continue without this move.} (9... Nb6 {is met with} 10. Nf4 Nxc4 11. Bxc4 bxc4 12. h5 {± And funnily enough this is the same position as in the Panno variation! Only that there, the knight arrived to c4 from a5, in this chapter, from b6.}) 10. O-O-O Bb7 {This is a good way to keep the tension for the moment, also it fights against g4, as it puts more pressure on the e4 pawn.} 11. Kb1 {A good reply; now cxb5 is threatened, as we defended a2.} (11. g4 $5 {is a very messy continuation, for the brave hearted this can be an interesting alternative to look into.}) 11... c5 {This seems like the most logical continuation.} 12. Bh6 {Another conceptual idea, usually in the Dragon structure or the King's Indian when Black has a very active bishop on g7, White simply trades it down.} b4 13. Nd5 e6 14. Bxg7 {This is simplest. Even if material is reduced, the positional advantage is conserved.} Kxg7 15. Nxf6 Nxf6 16. Qe3 $14 {[%cal Ge4e5,Ge2c1,Gf1e2] Black has issues to solve on the dark squares, e5 is a threat so is dxc5. White probably changes focus in the center with moves like Nc1-Be2 for the moment, but in the long run, don't forget that g4 can be a possibility.} *

