1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Nge2 a6 7. Be3 Nbd7 {The system with 6...a6 and 7...Nbd7 is an interesting way to approach the Saemisch, that was also recommended by Jones Gawain in his Chessable Course about the King's Indian. There are some lines that are very wild, but I will try to tame them a bit, in order to preserve our positional trumps for a long-term advantage.} 8. Qd2 ({Now} 8. h4 {would make little sense, because the last developing move of Black can't be punished concretely.}) 8... b5 9. h4 {Now, this move is a good idea, Black committed to playing ...b5, so we as well can start our counterplay on the kingside.} (9. cxb5 {I don't recommend you to take this pawn, Black is fast at organizing counterplay against White's center.} axb5 10. Nxb5 c6 11. Nbc3 e5 {...d5 is coming next, with a very unclear battle ahead.} 12. Ng3 d5 {∞ .}) 9... h5 {Black can't really continue without this move.} (9... Nb6 {is met with} 10. Nf4 Nxc4 11. Bxc4 bxc4 12. h5 {± And funnily enough this is the same position as in the Panno variation! Only that there, the knight arrived to c4 from a5, in this chapter, from b6.}) 10. O-O-O e5 {This is Black's idea, the knight on d7 is well suited for this central push.} (10... Nb6 11. Nf4 $1 {I cannot emphasize enough how important this move is. The knight is very safe here, ...e5 is not even possible now.} Nxc4 12. Bxc4 bxc4 13. g4 {This is strong, but actually, we are again transposing to the Panno Variation.} Bxg4 14. fxg4 Nxg4 15. Rdg1 {You already probably know what is our next move, but this can be found in the chapter about the Panno Variation.}) 11. d5 {We need to close down the potential of Black's g7 bishop.} Nb6 $5 {This is an interesting trade offer, White has no choice but to accept.} 12. Bxb6 {Of course White takes, otherwise ...Nc4 is an issue.} cxb6 13. cxb5 axb5 14. Nxb5 {This is a simpler way of playing. White is just using their positional advantage on the light squares.} Rxa2 15. Nec3 {We are not afraid of the trade on d1. It even helps White I would say.} Ra8 16. Bd3 {The king is actually very safe on the queenside. Just watch out if ...Nxd5 and ...e4 resources are available. If not, Black's kingside pieces are quite useless.} Bd7 17. b4 $1 {A good move, to take away the a5 and c5 squares and also give some air to the king on c1.} (17. Nxd6 $2 {This is a serious mistake.} Qe7 $1 {-+ Suddenly, the queen comes to b4, and with a lot of pressure on the king, White is borderline lost here.}) 17... Ne8 18. Kb2 $36 {White has a pleasant initiative here, a good plan would be to trade a pair of rooks watch out to not blunder the h4 pawn when doing so. Black doesn't have an active plan, and ideally White would like to achieve a knight vs bishop on g7 endgame. I believe in White's long-term chances here.} *

