1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is the initial move of our course. It’s a very ambitious continuation because we aim to gain full control of the center by playing 4. e4.} Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Nge2 a6 7. Be3 Nbd7 {The system with 6...a6 and 7...Nbd7 is an interesting way to approach the Saemisch, that was also recommended by Jones Gawain in his Chessable Course about the King's Indian. There are some lines that are very wild, but I will try to tame them a bit, in order to preserve our positional trumps for a long-term advantage.} 8. Qd2 ({Now} 8. h4 {would make little sense, because the last developing move of Black can't be punished concretely.}) 8... b5 9. h4 {Now, this move is a good idea, Black committed to playing ...b5, so we as well can start our counterplay on the kingside.} (9. cxb5 {I don't recommend you to take this pawn, Black is fast at organizing counterplay against White's center.} axb5 10. Nxb5 c6 11. Nbc3 e5 {...d5 is coming next, with a very unclear battle ahead.} 12. Ng3 d5 {∞ .}) 9... h5 {Black can't really continue without this move.} (9... Nb6 {is met with} 10. Nf4 Nxc4 11. Bxc4 bxc4 12. h5 {± And funnily enough this is the same position as in the Panno variation! Only that there, the knight arrived to c4 from a5, in this chapter, from b6.}) 10. O-O-O e5 {This is Black's idea, the knight on d7 is well suited for this central push.} (10... Nb6 11. Nf4 $1 {I cannot emphasize enough how important this move is. The knight is very safe here, ...e5 is not even possible now.} Nxc4 12. Bxc4 bxc4 13. g4 {This is strong, but actually, we are again transposing to the Panno Variation.} Bxg4 14. fxg4 Nxg4 15. Rdg1 {You already probably know what is our next move, but this can be found in the chapter about the Panno Variation.}) 11. d5 {We need to close down the potential of Black's g7 bishop.} bxc4 {This is the move recommended by Jones in his course.} 12. Nb1 $3 {[%cal Ge2c3,Gb1a3,Ga3c4] This is the key move you need to remember. The knight on c3 leaves room for the other knight on e2 to come to c3 in his place. Meanwhile, the knight on b1 has a good future on c4.} Nc5 {[%cal Gc5d3] A strong reply, with the idea to jump to d3.} (12... Nb6 {This is too naive, White anyway will manage to capture the pawn.} 13. Nec3 {± as in Basso-Silva Lucena, Seville 2024. White has a big positional advantage here. The play on the queenside and especially the c6 square, were decisive in that game.}) 13. Bxc5 {This is a strong move, the light squares bishop is more valuable for us.} (13. Nec3 {looks more logical, because it's hard psychologically to give up the dark squares bishop, but concretely it is less interesting.} Nd3+ 14. Bxd3 cxd3 15. Qxd3 Ne8 {With ... f5 next.}) 13... dxc5 14. Nec3 $14 {[%cal Gd2e3,Gb1d2,Gd2c4] Qe3-Nd2-Nxc4 next. Black's position is dangerous from a positional point of view.} (14. Nec3 {A sample line could be} Ne8 15. Qe3 Nd6 16. Nd2 Nb5 17. Bxc4 Nd4 18. Kb1 {⩲ (It is true that Black got a strong knight on d4, but White can play around it, the other important factor is that the king on b1 is safer than the one on g8.Don't forget that g4 is still on the cards. Another interesting point could be to get a Na4-Nb3 configuration, to put maximum pressure on the c5 pawn. I like White's chances here, and the engine also agrees +0.50.)}) *

