[White "Introduction: 3.f3 Against King's Indian/Benoni Defense"]
[Black "3.f3 Against King's Indian/Benoni Defense"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A65"]
[PlyCount "22"]
[GameId "2160984184107125"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 c5 4. d5 e6 {As we saw in the 'Move Order Training', Black has a lot of different move orders, but the final position at move nine will always be the same.} 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 d6 7. e4 Bg7 8. Nge2 O-O 9. Ng3 {This is the starting position for the KID/Benoni. In the second part of the introduction, we will explore all the possible move orders that lead to this position. We play 9. Ng3 not because the knight is particularly strong on this square, but to complete our development with 10. Be2 followed by 11. O-O.Often, we will need to reposition our knight from g3, and there are typically two options: Nh1-Nf2 f2 is an excellent square for the knight in the Saemisch variation, as we will see, or Nf1-Ne3 where the knight is well-placed on e3, ready to jump to c4.If you choose the latter maneuver, it's advisable to do so after playing Be2 and before O-O, ensuring the f1 square is free.} a6 (9... h5 {Black can also play 9...h5 without including the moves 9...a6 and 10.a4; we will analyze this option in Chapter 14.}) 10. a4 {The moves 9...a6 and 10. a4 are often played automatically by both players, but in this course, we will see that this sequence is extremely significant. Whether these moves are included or not will have a profound impact on the game for both sides.} h5 {Black's second most popular move. It is logical for Black to play against our knight on g3, since it may not have a lot of retreat squares.} 11. Be2 {We are not concerned about h5-h4 at this moment. Since we have not yet castled, our knight can retreat to f1. From f1, it can move to e3 and eventually reach the excellent c4 square.} (11. Bg5 {is another possible move, with the idea to stop h5-h4. We will speak about this move in a separate Chapter.}) 11... Nh7 {This is Black's best continuation, in my opinion; we will analyze it in Chapter 13.} (11... h4 {This would be Black's most natural continuation; we will analyze it in Chapter 12.}) (11... Nbd7 12. Bg5 {This line, along with some other minor sidelines, will be analyzed in Chapter 15.}) *

