1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 c5 4. d5 e6 {As we saw in the 'Move Order Training', Black has a lot of different move orders, but the final position at move nine will always be the same.} 5. e4 d6 {[%cal Gd6e5,Re4e5] Black prevents e4-e5 ideas.} 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Nge2 {[%cal Ge2g3] White's plan is to develop the knight to g3.} O-O 8. Ng3 exd5 9. cxd5 {This is the main position of the KID/Benoni variations.} a6 10. a4 h5 {Black's second most popular move. It is logical for Black to play against our knight on g3, since it may not have a lot of retreat squares.} 11. Be2 {We are not concerned about h5-h4 at this moment. Since we have not yet castled, our knight can retreat to f1. From f1, it can move to e3 and eventually reach the excellent c4 square.} (11. Bg5 {is another possible move, with the idea to stop h5-h4. We will speak about this move in a separate Chapter.}) 11... h4 {In this chapter, we will examine the consequences of this logical continuation. As I mentioned earlier, we do not fear this move, but it remains a serious option for Black.} 12. Nf1 {Now, Black reaches a big crossroads; essentially, they must choose between two plans: one is to ignore White's idea of going Bg5 that targets the h4 pawn and focus on achieving ... b7-b5, the other one is to retreat the f6 knight, this way protecting the g5 square and focus on the ...f7-f5 push eventually.} Nh5 $4 {This is a very famous mistake. It would be Black's most natural move, but it simply doesn't work because of g4.} 13. g4 $1 (13. g4 {And Black has nothing better than to retreat by playing} Nf6 {because it is too dangerous to open the h file.}) 13... Nf6 (13... hxg3 14. hxg3 {With g4 next and White's h file is fatal for Black.}) 14. Bg5 h3 15. Ne3 $16 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4,Gf3,Gg4] Black is suffocated by the e4-g4 bind, and also they have lost too many tempi.} *

