1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 c5 4. d5 e6 {As we saw in the 'Move Order Training', Black has a lot of different move orders, but the final position at move nine will always be the same.} 5. e4 d6 {Black prevents e4-e5 ideas.} 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Nge2 {White's plan is to develop the knight to g3.} O-O 8. Ng3 exd5 9. cxd5 {This is the main position of the KID/Benoni variations.} a6 10. a4 h5 {Black's second most popular move. It is logical for Black to play against our knight on g3, since it may not have a lot of retreat squares.} 11. Be2 {We are not concerned about h5-h4 at this moment. Since we have not yet castled, our knight can retreat to f1. From f1, it can move to e3 and eventually reach the excellent c4 square.} (11. Bg5 {is another possible move, with the idea to stop h5-h4. We will speak about this move in a separate Chapter.}) 11... h4 {In this chapter, we will examine the consequences of this logical continuation. As I mentioned earlier, we do not fear this move, but it remains a serious option for Black.} 12. Nf1 {Now, Black reaches a big crossroads; essentially, they must choose between two plans: one is to ignore White's idea of going Bg5 that targets the h4 pawn and focus on achieving ... b7-b5, the other one is to retreat the f6 knight, this way protecting the g5 square and focus on the ...f7-f5 push eventually.} Re8 {This might seem like a normal useful move, but in fact it is much worse than 12...Nbd7.} 13. Bg5 h3 14. g4 $1 {We are happy to grab some space since, comparing to what we will see in the 12...Nbd7 line, Black is not ready now for the b7-b5 push.} Nbd7 15. Ne3 Rb8 16. O-O {Comparing to 12...Nbd7 we have included the moves O-O and Re8, which favours us, let's just check to be sure what happens after the typical continuation} b5 17. axb5 axb5 18. Bxb5 Nxg4 {The typical queen sacrifice doesn't help Black here.} (18... Ne5 {is impossible due to the hanging rook.}) 19. Bxd8 Nxe3 20. Bc7 {We return the queen, but with interests.} Nxd1 21. Bxb8 $18 {White shouldn't experience any trouble in converting this position into a full point.} *

