1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 c5 4. d5 e6 {As we saw in the 'Move Order Training', Black has a lot of different move orders, but the final position at move nine will always be the same.} 5. e4 d6 {Black prevents e4-e5 ideas.} 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Nge2 {White's plan is to develop the knight to g3.} O-O 8. Ng3 exd5 9. cxd5 {This is the main position of the KID/Benoni variations.} a6 10. a4 h5 {Black's second most popular move. It is logical for Black to play against our knight on g3, since it may not have a lot of retreat squares.} 11. Be2 {We are not concerned about h5-h4 at this moment. Since we have not yet castled, our knight can retreat to f1. From f1, it can move to e3 and eventually reach the excellent c4 square.} (11. Bg5 {is another possible move, with the idea to stop h5-h4. We will speak about this move in a separate Chapter.}) 11... h4 {In this chapter, we will examine the consequences of this logical continuation. As I mentioned earlier, we do not fear this move, but it remains a serious option for Black.} 12. Nf1 {Now, Black reaches a big crossroads; essentially, they must choose between two plans: one is to ignore White's idea of going Bg5 that targets the h4 pawn and focus on achieving ... b7-b5, the other one is to retreat the f6 knight, this way protecting the g5 square and focus on the ...f7-f5 push eventually.} Nbd7 {This is the best according to the engines.} 13. Bg5 h3 {Now White has to take an important decision. Usually the options are g3, g4, gxh3 or the more sophisticated Ne3-hxg2-Rg1.} 14. g4 {would be our typical reaction, as we have seen also in the 12...Re8 line. But now it doesn't work so well.} Rb8 $1 {In my opinion in this KID/Benoni saemisch positions Black's best plan is b7-b5.} 15. Ne3 b5 (15... Qc7 {This makes no sense here, but it will be strong in the 14. g3 line.} 16. O-O Nh7 17. Bh4 {⩲ Comparing to 14. g3, we can always play Bg3 here.}) 16. axb5 axb5 {Black has a good game no matter how we take.} 17. Bxb5 (17. Nxb5 Qb6 $1 {Supporting Ba6 idea.} 18. Bf4 {(( 18.Qc2 Ba6= ∞ )) (( 18.Na3?? Nxe4 19.fxe4 Qb4+ 20.Kf2 Qxe4 -+ 21.Qd3 Qe5 ))} Ne5 19. Bxe5 dxe5 20. Na3 Qxb2 21. Kf2 Bh6 22. Nac4 Qd4 {⩱ Comparing to 14. g3 here Black's Bh6 is much stronger as it has potential to go Bg5-Bh4+.}) 17... Ne5 (17... Nxg4 $5 {Also possible, be careful about such tactics.} 18. Bxd8 Nxe3 19. Qd2 Ng2+ 20. Kd1 Rxd8 {With 2 pieces for the queen, but even according to the engine, Black has a huge compensation. This is because all the pieces are very active, and we have potential problems with our king.}) 18. O-O Bd7 19. Bxd7 Qxd7 {Black has a very good compensation.} *

