1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 c5 4. d5 e6 {As we saw in the 'Move Order Training', Black has a lot of different move orders, but the final position at move nine will always be the same.} 5. e4 d6 {Black prevents e4-e5 ideas.} 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Nge2 {White's plan is to develop the knight to g3.} O-O 8. Ng3 exd5 9. cxd5 {This is the main position of the KID/Benoni variations.} a6 10. a4 h5 {Black's second most popular move. It is logical for Black to play against our knight on g3, since it may not have a lot of retreat squares.} 11. Be2 {We are not concerned about h5-h4 at this moment. Since we have not yet castled, our knight can retreat to f1. From f1, it can move to e3 and eventually reach the excellent c4 square.} (11. Bg5 {is another possible move, with the idea to stop h5-h4. We will speak about this move in a separate Chapter.}) 11... h4 {In this chapter, we will examine the consequences of this logical continuation. As I mentioned earlier, we do not fear this move, but it remains a serious option for Black.} 12. Nf1 {Now, Black reaches a big crossroads; essentially, they must choose between two plans: one is to ignore White's idea of going Bg5 that targets the h4 pawn and focus on achieving ... b7-b5, the other one is to retreat the f6 knight, this way protecting the g5 square and focus on the ...f7-f5 push eventually.} Nbd7 {This is the best according to the engines.} 13. Bg5 h3 {Now White has to take an important decision. Usually the options are g3, g4, gxh3 or the more sophisticated Ne3-hxg2-Rg1.} 14. gxh3 $1 {To understand why it is the best, we had to compare it with other options.} Rb8 (14... Qc7 {Black now wants to continue with Nh5, but we can prevent this idea by playing.} 15. Ng3 {⩲}) 15. Ne3 $1 {This is still the best square for our knight.} (15. Ng3 $6 {has been chosen by Ivanchuk, but here Black has his typical break.} b5 $1 16. axb5 axb5 17. Nxb5 Qb6 {Black has full compensation.}) 15... Re8 {[%cal Gd7f8,Gf8h7] Black's idea is Nf8-N8h7, but they are not in time.} 16. h4 $1 Nf8 17. h5 $1 N8h7 (17... gxh5 $2 {would be suicide as after} 18. Rg1 {+- White is already winning.}) 18. Bh4 g5 19. h6 $1 {A very important move. The idea is that Black's bishop on h6 will be misplaced.} (19. Bg3 $2 {The same line is not working if we don't include the moves h6-Bxh6.} Nxh5 20. Nc4 b5 21. axb5 axb5 22. Nxd6 Nxg3 23. Nxf7 Qf6 24. hxg3 Qxf7 {-+}) 19... Bxh6 20. Bg3 Nh5 21. Nc4 $1 b5 {The critical continuation.} 22. axb5 axb5 23. Nxd6 $1 {White accepts the challenge.} Nxg3 24. Nxf7 $1 ({It's an important intermezzo. In the case of} 24. hxg3 $2 {, after} Qxd6 {, White has no compensation for the missing piece.}) 24... Qf6 $2 {Thanks to the inclusion of the moves h6-Bxh6, White is much better.} 25. hxg3 {The move Qxf7 is not possible because Bh6 is hanging.} Kxf7 26. d6 $18 {[%cal Ga1a7] And White is already winning as they have too many threats, for example Ra7+.} *

