{[%evp 0,47,19,31,14,-14,43,-7,25,5,66,66,66,57,61,37,45,36,34,34,48,21,58,43,54,53,74,89,75,78,98,98,167,132,111,146,74,109,140,140,131,137,135,157,175,177,160,154,144,142]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 c5 4. d5 e6 {As we saw in the 'Move Order Training', Black has a lot of different move orders, but the final position at move nine will always be the same.} 5. e4 d6 {Black prevents e4-e5 ideas.} 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Nge2 {White's plan is to develop the knight to g3.} O-O 8. Ng3 exd5 9. cxd5 {This is the main position of the KID/Benoni variations.} a6 10. a4 h5 {Black's second most popular move. It is logical for Black to play against our knight on g3, since it may not have a lot of retreat squares.} 11. Be2 {We are not concerned about h5-h4 at this moment. Since we have not yet castled, our knight can retreat to f1. From f1, it can move to e3 and eventually reach the excellent c4 square.} (11. Bg5 {is another possible move, with the idea to stop h5-h4. We will speak about this move in a separate Chapter.}) 11... h4 {In this chapter, we will examine the consequences of this logical continuation. As I mentioned earlier, we do not fear this move, but it remains a serious option for Black.} 12. Nf1 {Now, Black reaches a big crossroads; essentially, they must choose between two plans: one is to ignore White's idea of going Bg5 that targets the h4 pawn and focus on achieving ... b7-b5, the other one is to retreat the f6 knight, this way protecting the g5 square and focus on the ...f7-f5 push eventually.} Nbd7 {This is the best according to the engines.} 13. Bg5 h3 {Now White has to take an important decision. Usually the options are g3, g4, gxh3 or the more sophisticated Ne3-hxg2-Rg1.} 14. gxh3 $1 {To understand why it is the best, we had to compare it with other options.} Rb8 (14... Qc7 {Black now wants to continue with Nh5, but we can prevent this idea by playing.} 15. Ng3 {⩲}) 15. Ne3 $1 {This is still the best square for our knight.} (15. Ng3 $6 {has been chosen by Ivanchuk, but here Black has his typical break.} b5 $1 16. axb5 axb5 17. Nxb5 Qb6 {Black has full compensation.}) 15... b5 (15... Qc7 {Of course now we don't fear Nh7-g5 ideas, as our bishop has many squares compared to the 14. g3 line.} 16. O-O Nh7 17. Bh4 {±}) 16. axb5 {Here White should remember some lines, but keep in mind that this position was never seen in practice.} axb5 17. Nxb5 Qb6 {Black defends the d6 pawn and at the same time unpins the knight on f6.} 18. Na3 {Black has some moves, but none of them leads to equality.} Qxb2 {The most natural move, Black takes back one pawn, but it allows us to consolidate faster.} 19. Nac4 Qd4 {And now White has the strong Nc2!} {.sjy} 20. Nc2 $1 {[%csl Rd4] That challenges Black's queen.} Qxd1+ {Black should better trade the queens, but the endgame does not look promising.} (20... Qc3+ $2 {It's understandable that Black doesn't want to exchange queens, but after} 21. Bd2 Qb3 22. Ra3 {± Black's d6 pawn is falling.}) 21. Rxd1 Ba6 $1 {Black has to be very precise in order to keep some compensation for the missing pawn.} 22. Nxd6 Rb6 $1 (22... Bxe2 $2 23. Kxe2 Rb2 24. Rd2 {±}) 23. Bxa6 Rxa6 24. Nc4 {This is quite unpleasant. Yes, Black has some compensation, the engine will hold for sure, but from the practical point of view they still need to work a lot being 2 pawns down.} *

